Dr. [**NAME**],ENT team and Dr. [**NAME**],NICU team were present at delivery  Procedure: The patient was identified and brought to the operating room. After satisfactory anesthesia, the patient was prepped and draped in a routine fashion for abdominal surgery.  Time-out confirmed patient and procedure.  It was confirmed that she had received her prophylactic antibiotics and that her sequential compression stockings were in place and functioning. The abdomen was entered with a Pfannensteil approach.  The subcutaneous tissue was dissected up to the fascia. The fascia was incised in the midline and  extended bilaterally by the mayo scissors. The rectus muscles were separated from the overlying rectus sheath superiorly and inferiorly. The rectus was then separated in the midline and peritoneum entered carefully. A self retaining retractor was placed. A bladder flap was not created and then an approximately 4cm transverse incision was made in the lower uterine segment with a scalpel. The amniotic membrane was separated from the uterine muscle circumferentially, being careful not to disrupt the membrane prematurely.The retainer portion of the hysterotomy stapler (Premium poly CS-Covidien) was introduced initially on the left all the time lifting the tips of the retainer up against the uterine muscle to avoid inadvertently injuring any fetal tissues. The hysterotomy stappler was fired once it was clear the retainer was clear of uterine vessels and fetal tissue. The stappler was then replaced and reloaded with the same procedure performed on maternal right of the hysterotomy. The fetal head was delivered through the hysterotomy into the intact amniotic sac. Once the fetal head was delivered through the hysterotomy, the amniotic sac was ruptured, fluid was clear.  The infant was delivered cephalic up to the level of both arms and Dr [**NAME**] with his ENT team intubated the infant uneventfully. Upon completion, the umbilical cord was clamped and cut,blood for gases and DNA obtained  with baby handed to the waiting pediatricians. .  The placenta was delivered with cord traction.  The uterus was wiped out with a lap.  The uterus was closed in a double layer closure using two layers of 0- vicryl.  The fascia was closed with 1 suture/s of 0-Vicryl starting at the angle and running in a continuous fashion. The subcutaneous tissue was irrigated and reapproximated with interrupted sutures of 2-0 chromic.  The skin was closed with 4-0 monocryl.  Dermabond was applied.  The vagina was cleared of clots.  All counts were correct and the patient left for the recovery room in good condition.  [**NAME**] MD  I was present for the entire case.  I reviewed the resident's note and made appropriate corrections and additions to it.   [**NAME**], M.D. Maternal Fetal Medicine Fellow Adjunct Clinical Associate Department of Obstetrics and Gynecology [**LOCATION_INSTITUTE**] College of Medicine

Indication: [**NAME**] is a 26 y.o. female, Para4004 status post vaginal delivery who requests permanent sterilization by tubal interruption.   Procedure: After satisfactory anesthesia, the patient was prepped and draped in a routine fashion for abdominal surgery.  Time out confirmed the patient and procedure.  The abdomen was entered with a transverse incision below the umbilicus.  Stay sutures of 0-Vicryl were placed through the fascia on either side of the incision.  The right fallopian tube was identified by the fimbria and a loop ligated with #1-plain gut suture.  A small defect was made in the mesosalpinx within the loop and each side of the tube double ligated with 0-chromic suture. The intervening segment was excised.  Presence of lumen was confirmed in the excised segment.  Each end of the remaining tube was made hemostatic with cautery.  The exact same procedure was repeated on the left fallopian tube.   The fascia was closed by reapproximating the stay sutures of O-Vicryl.  The skin was closed with a subcuticular stitch of 3-0 monocryl.  Dermabond was applied.  All counts were correct and the patient left for the recovery room in satisfactory condition.    There were no complications of the procedure.  [**NAME**]  Dictated for E. Wyckoff

At the completion of the procedure, there was no suture in the rectum.   Indication:  [**NAME**] is a 30 y.o. P0020 who delivered via vaginal delivery complicated by a third degree laceration   Details of Procedure:  The patient was placed in lithotomy position. The perineum was cleansed with betadine at the beginning of the repair, periodically throughout the repair, and at the end of the repair. Each free end of the capsule was grasped with an Allis clamp. Four figure of eight sutures of 0- vicryl were used to reapproximate the capsule. A running locking suture of 2-0 chromic was used to close the vaginal tissue defect beginning at the apex and continuing to the hymenal ring. A crown suture was placed. The dead space between either side of the laceration was closed with 2-0 chromic, and the skin was reapproximated using a subcuticular suture of 2-0 vicryl.  At the completion of the procedure, a rectal exam was performed and there were no defects noted. There was no suture in the rectum.   An xray was performed due to incorrect lap count. The Xray resulted as "No evidence for retained sponge markers."  H [**NAME**]  MD

SPECIMENS TO PATHOLOGY: placenta, bilateral portions of fallopian tubes  INDICATIONS: [**NAME**] is a 28 y.o. female para 3032 with history of PPROM since 20 weeks who was hospitalized with intermittent bleeding concerning for marginal abruption began to have abdominal pain, contractions, and repetitive variable decelerations. She had received steroids at 24 and 27 weeks. Decision was made to proceed with cesarean delivery and magnesium was restarted for neuroprotection. Due to more prolonged and deeper variables, the procedure was carried out in stat fashion but with ability to obtain quick spinal anesthesia beforehand.   DESCRIPTION OF THE PROCEDURE: The patient was identified and brought to the operating room and placed on the operating table.  A time-out was taken and the patient's identity and planned surgical procedure were confirmed.  After the establishment of adequate regional anesthesia, the patient was placed in the dorsal supine position in left lateral tilt and her abdomen was prepped and draped in the usual sterile manner.  A second time-out was taken and the patient's identity and planned surgical procedure were confirmed; it was confirmed that her antibiotics were being administered and that her pneumatic compression stockings were in place and functioning.   The abdomen was entered in the routine manner through a Pfannenstiel incision. The incision was taken down to the level of the fascia which was incised in the midline. The incision was extended laterally in either direction over the rectus muscles. The fascia was dissected off the rectus muscle bluntly. The rectus muscle was divided bluntly. The peritoneum was entered in a clear space bluntly and a few adhesions overlying the anterior lower uterine segment were taken down.  A bladder flap was not created. The lower uterine segment was examined closely and not felt to be adequate to support a low transverse uterine incision. A vertical incision was made in the lower uterine segment with a scalpel and the incision was extended bilaterally with bandage scissors.  The amniotic fluid was scant but clear.  The above described infant was delivered from the Breech presentation.  The cord was doubly clamped after very brief delay and milking of the cord and cut and the baby was handed to the awaiting pediatrician. A sample of cord and cord blood was obtained for analysis.  The placenta was delivered with gentle traction on the cord, and the uterine cavity was cleared with a clean lap. The placenta was falling apart and with adherent blood clot. The uterus was exteriorized, and the uterine incision was closed in 3 layers, the first a runnig suture of 0-vicryl and the second a running, imbricating suture of 0-vicryl. A third baseball stitch was placed incorporating the uterine serosa.  The right fallopian tube was identified by the fimbria, double ligated with 0-chromic suture and the intervening segment excised.  The left fallopian tube was identified by the fimbria, double ligated with 0-chromic suture and the intervening segment excised.     The uterus was replaced in the abdominal cavity.  Adequate hemostasis was confirmed along the uterine incision, posterior to the bladder, and in the subfascial area.  The fascia was closed with one suture of 0 Vicryl beginning from one end of the incision and running continuously.  The subcutaneous tissue was irrigated and re-approximated with a running suture of 3-0 Vicryl.  The skin was closed with a running subcuticular closure of 3-0 monocryl. Dermabond was applied to the incision.  The vagina was cleared of clots.  All counts were correct and the patient left for the recovery room in good condition. The abdomen was entered with a Pfannenstiel approach and dissected down to the level of the fascia with sharp dissection and cautery. Amniotic fluid was clear at the time of ROM.  The above described infant was delivered from the Cephalic presentation with assistance of a Kiwi vaccum.  The cord was clamped and cut and the baby handed to the pediatrician.  Blood for gases and DNA was obtained. An attempt was made to collect cord blood, but the placenta was already separating and only a small sample was obtained. The placenta was delivered with cord traction.  The uterus was then wiped out with a lap.  Ring forceps were placed on the angles of the hysterotomy as well as the upper and lower sections of the uterus.  The uterus was closed in a single layer closure using 0-Monocryl. The uterine incision was hemostatic and uterine tone adequate. Attention was then turned to the tubal ligation. The right fallopian tube was grasped with a Babcock and identified by its fimbriated end.  A small defect was made in the mesosalpinx below the grasped segment.  The tube was then doubly ligated with 0-Gut suture and the intervening segment excised.  The remaining tubal segments were hemostatic.  The same procedure was repeated on the left fallopian tube.  Portions of both tubes were passed off the surgical field and sent to pathology. The Alexis O-Ring retractor was removed.  The fascia was inspected superiorly and inferiorly and was found to be intact and hemostatic.  A Fish visceral retainer was placed below the level of the fascia to ensure safe closure.  The fascia was closed with 2 sutures of 0-Vicryl starting at the angles and running in a continuous fashion to meet the midline. The Fish retractor was removed prior to final fascial  Closure.  The subcutaneous tissue was irrigated and made hemostatic with cautery.  The subcutaneous tissue was closed in 2 layers with 2-0 Vicryl.  The first layer contained interrupted sutures and the second layer was running.  The skin was closed with a running subcuticular stitch of 3-0 Monocryl.  Steri strips and a Bioguard dressing were applied.  The vagina was cleared of clots.  All counts were correct and the patient left for the recovery room in good condition. Fetal biocoronal craniosynostosis  Postoperative Diagnosis: Same, delivered  Operation Performed:  Repeat Low Transverse Cesarean Section  Surgeon: [**NAME**]  Assisstant: [**NAME**]  Anesthesiologist: [**NAME**]  Anesthesiology Assisstant: [**NAME**]  Anesthesia: Spinal  Pathology: Placenta, Portion of bilateral fallopian tubes  EBL: 700mL  UOP:  100mL  Fluids:  2000cc crystalloid  Findings: Grossly normal uterus with uterine window in the lower uterine segment, Normal tubes and ovaries bilaterally. Indication: [**NAME**] is a 26 y.o. female para 2123 who presented to L&D at 37 weeks gestation for scheduled repeat cesarean delivery.  She was consented and taken to the operating room for the above noted procedures.  Prior to surgery it was confirmed that she still desired permanent surgical sterilization.  Procedure: After satisfactory anesthesia, the patient was prepped and draped in a routine fashion for abdominal surgery.  Time-out confirmed patient and procedure.  The abdomen was entered with a Pfannenstiel approach and dissected down to the level of the fascia with sharp dissection and cautery. The fascia was scored in the midline and extended laterally with sharp dissection. The anterior leaf of the fascia was grasped upwards and the underlying rectus muscle was dissected with sharp and blunt dissection. The superior segment of fascia was tightly adhered to the underlying rectus muscle, therefore entry to the peritoneal cavity was achieved during separation of these layers.  This inferior segment of fascia was then grawped downwards and the underlying rectus muscle dissected. The bilateral rectus muscles were dissected horizontally to make room for delivery and the underlying uterus was exposed.  A bladder flap was not created due to an extremely thin lower uterine segment with uterine window present.  A transverse incision was made in the lower uterine segment (above the prior hysterotomy sites) with a scalpel and extended laterally with blunt dissection.  Amniotic fluid was clear at the time of rupture.  The above described infant was delivered from the Cephalic presentation and gave a spontaneous cry.  The cord was clamped and cut and the baby handed to the pediatrician.  Blood for gases and DNA was obtained then cord blood donatino was performed.  The placenta was delivered with cord traction.  The uterus was then exteriorized and wiped out with a lap. The uterus was closed in a single locked layer using O-Monocryl.  Attention was then turned to the tubal ligation.  A portion of the right fallopian tube was grasped in the mid-isthmic section and a defect made in the nearby mesosalpinx.  The portion of tube was double ligated with 0-Chromic and the intervening segment excised.  Hemostasis of the remaining portions was ensured.  The same procedure was repeated on the left fallopian tube. The peritoneal cavity was suctioned over a clea lap. The uterus was placed back into the peritoneal cavity. The uterine incision was hemostatic and uterine tone adequate. The fascia was inspected superiorly and inferiorly and was found to be intact and hemostatic.  The fascia was closed with 1 suture of 0-Vicryl starting at the angle and running in a continuous fashion to the opposite side. The subcutaneous tissue was irrigated and closed with 3 interrupted sutures of 0-Chromic.  The skin was closed with a running subcuticular stitch of 3-0 Monocryl.  Dermabond was applied.  The vagina was cleared of clots.  All counts were correct and the patient left for the recovery room in good condition.  [**NAME**], MD

Department of Obstetrics and Gynecology Gynecologic Surgery  Post Operative Note    [**NAME**] [**DATE**] 2:24 PM    Preoperative Diagnosis:  1. Undesired Fertility  Post-operative Diagnosis: 1. Same  Procedure performed: 1. Bilateral Partial Salpingectomy  Surgeons: Dr [**NAME**]  Assistants:   Anesthesia Attending:   Anesthesia Assistant:   Anesthesia:  spinal  EBL: 15 cc  Fluids:   PRBC  Crystalloid    Platelets  Other    Urinary Output:  see anesthesia note  Drains: 1.foley to gravity    Implants (include size & make): none  Specimens: bilateral fallopian tubes  Findings:  Normal pelvis   Complications: The patient tolerated the procedure well with no complications.  Disposition: stable  Operative Report and Findings: The patient was taken to the operating room and there under spinal anesthesia her abdomen was draped and prepped in the usual sterile fashion.  A semicircular incision was made under the umbilicus and the various anatomical layers were dissected down to the layer of the parietal peritoneum.The parietal peritoneum was entered with aid of hemostats and Metzenbaum scissors.   There was good hemostasis.  The left fallopian tube was isolated with the aid of singlet forceps and the army navy retractors.  The left fallopian tube was grasped in the mid portion with a balcock clamp.  A hole was cauterized in the mesosalpinx.  The surgeon then tied 2  000 vicryl sutures on either side of the tube and the midportion was resected.  The surgeon then tied a 00 silk suture over the distal part of the proximal stump.  The same procedure was performed on the contralateral side.  There was good hemostasis and the closure of the abdomen was begun.  The parietal peritoneum was then closed with a continuous layer of 000-vicryl.   The fascia was closed with a series of 0-Monocril popoffs starting a suture from both corners of the incision.  The subcutaneous layer was closed with a continuous layer of 000-vicryl.  The skin was closed with a subcuticular stitch of 0000-proline suture.  The incision was covered with a Derma bond dressing.  Hemostasis was excellent at all levels.  The patient tolerated the procedure well under spinal anesthesia.  She was taken to the recovery room in satisfactory condition. LTM - Continuous Video Electroencephalography Note   Date of Service: [**DATE**]  Indications: status epilepticus  History: 20 y/o F who is 28 weeks pregnant with embolic L MCA stroke in [**DATE**] (due to IV drug abuse), presents with multiple breakthrough sGTCs.  Technical Summary: This is a long-term monitoring EEG performed in the inpatient setting from 05:37 am on [**DATE**] through 06:10 am on [**DATE**] utilizing a 17-channel digital videoEEG system. A standard set of electrodes were applied according to International 10-20 guidelines with dual-lead EKG recording simultaneous cardiac rhythm. Standard techniques of continuous video EEG monitoring including computerized spike and seizure detection software, technologist review and time sampling as well as patient/staff-activated pushbutton alarms were utilized.   Report:  Background Predominant Frequency: continuous diffuse polymorphic delta frequency slowing  Superimposed Frequency: abundant 8 Hz nonposterior dominant alpha activity  Rhythmic or Periodic Patterns: yes, continuous midline and left central LPDs at 1-1.5 Hz, non-evolving, non-fluctuating.  Asymmetry in Amplitude or Frequency: yes, mild asymmetry of cerebral activity decreased left hemisphere  Breach rhythm: none  Epileptiform discharges: yes, LPDs see above.  Seizures: none  Voltage: normal  Variability: yes  Reactivity: unclear  Sleep: none  Stage II sleep transients (K-complexes and spindles): none  Continuity: continuous  EKG: NSR  Clinical interpretation: This 20 minute cvEEG recording in an intubated, sedated patient on an IV midazolam gtt is abnormal due to continuous lateralized periodic discharges (LPDs) over the midline and left central region which is consistent with an acute or subacute disturbance of cerebral function, structural lesion, and/or peri-/post-ictal state involving this region. LPDs are highly associated with partial seizures. There is a mild asymmetry of cerebral activity being of decreased amplitude over the left hemisphere. These findings are consistent with a focal disturbance of cerebral function or focal lesion involving this region. The background shows a severe degree of diffuse slowing with superimposed faster frequencies in the alpha range.  These findings are consistent with a generalized anesthetic pattern due to anesthetic effect.  No seizures were present during the recording. Compared to the previous cvEEG from [**DATE**], there is no significant change.  [**NAME**], M.D.

Lactation note The pt was breastfeeding at the time of my visit. She was slumped to the left side with the baby held in a football position. I inquired about her comfort level and she replied that she was not comfortable. I offered assistance which she readily accepted. The baby was held while she repositioned herself and removed her upper clothing to promote STS. The breasts were massaged and colostrum was expressed from both breasts. The nipples are well everted but very reddened and sore. The baby has a frenulum but intermittently is able to extend his tongue. He was noted to bite my gloved finger while sucking rhythmically. The baby was placed back on the left breast in a football hold with a deep latch using the nipple to nose practice. The baby was observed by both parents to suck consistently with his lips at a 90 degree angle. Pillows were used to improve the baby's body alignment and the mothers comfort. She reported a comfortable experience and felt the baby was nursing better. I reviewed the [**LOCATION_INSTITUTE**] breastfeeding booklet with the parents and provided them with my contact information.  [**NAME**] BSN, CLC

SPECIMENS TO PATHOLOGY: Placenta  INDICATIONS: 22 y.o. para @ 41w0d admitted in labor and augmented with pitocin. She progressed to 5cm dilation and had arrest of dilation despite adequate contractions for > 6 hours. She developed chorioamnionitis and was taken to the operating room for cesarean delivery.   DESCRIPTION OF THE PROCEDURE: The patient was identified and brought to the operating room and placed on the operating table.  A time-out was taken and the patient's identity and planned surgical procedure were confirmed.  After the establishment of adequate regional anesthesia, the patient was placed in the dorsal supine position in left lateral tilt and her abdomen was prepped and draped in the usual sterile manner.  A second time-out was taken and the patient's identity and planned surgical procedure were confirmed; it was confirmed that her antibiotics were being administered and that her pneumatic compression stockings were in place and functioning.   The abdomen was entered in the routine manner through a Pfannenstiel incision.  A bladder flap was created.  A transverse incision was made in the lower uterine segment with a scalpel and the incision was extended bilaterally with traction.  The amniotic fluid was clear.  The above described infant was delivered from the Cephalic presentation.  The cord was doubly clamped and cut, and the baby was handed to the awaiting pediatricians. A sample of cord and cord blood were obtained for analysis.  The placenta was delivered with gentle traction on the cord, and the uterine cavity was cleared with a clean lap.  The uterus was exteriorized, and the corners of the uterine incision were taken in figures of 8 with 0-vicryl and the uterus was closed in a single layer of 0 Vicryl.  The uterus was replaced in the abdominal cavity.  The fascia was closed with a suture of 0 Vicryl.  The subcutaneous tissue was irrigated with saline. The skin was closed with a subcuticular stitch of 4-0 Monocryl.  Dermabond was applied to the incision.  The vagina was cleared of clots.  All counts were correct and the patient left for the recovery room in good condition.  Dictated for Dr. [**NAME**], MD  I was present for the entire case.  I reviewed the resident's note and made appropriate corrections and additions to it. This note was copied from the chart of BABY/[**NAME**]. Lactation note:  In to see dyad. Mother very tired. Reports not sleeping at all last night d/t cluster feeding behavior and fussiness of infant. Also reports supplementing x1 via syringe. C/o very sore nipples.  Infant down 5% weight from birth. Enocuraged mother to supplement with her own milk vs formula if she chooses to supplement. I provided mother a container and syringe to use--encouraged her to call for assistance wtih hand expression and syringe feeding as needed.   Breasts soft round Nipples more everted than yesterday, short, intact, non damaged Infant tongue-short frenulum noted but nipple remains round most of the time after feeds, per mother.  Assisted mother to bf infant, as showing feeding cues. Mother positioned infant in cross cradle hold on left breast. Good latch noted. Mother c/o soreness greastest in the initial latch, but persisted throughout. Infant with good rhythmic sucking. I discussed my concern re:sore nipples at only 2 days after delivery may be due to shallow latch d/t short nipples vs infant pulling nipples more everted vs tongue tie issue.  In breastfeeding book discussed community resources including mary and teresa and encouraged to seek appt if soreness continues to persist past a few days post d/c, as soreness is not normal and may lead to low milk supply.   Encouraged bf on demand with unrestricted access to the breast with continued STS. Discussed infant feeding 8-10 times in 24 hours and normal cluster feeding behavior after the first 24 hours. Discouraged pacifiers, formula or artificial nipples due to the risk of low milk supply. Left phone number to call me for next feed or for any problems, questions, or concerns.

SPECIMENS TO PATHOLOGY:    ID Type Source Tests Collected by Time Destination  A :  Tissue Surg Path Fallopian Tube, Right OPTIME SURGICAL PATHOLOGY TISSUE [**NAME**], MD [**DATE**] 1507   B :  Tissue Surg Path Fallopian Tube, Left OPTIME SURGICAL PATHOLOGY TISSUE [**NAME**], MD [**DATE**] 1507      CLINICAL SUMMARY:  Ms. [**NAME**] is a 44 y.o., para 2103, at [**NAME**], EDD [**DATE**], by Ultrasound, who presented for repeat cesarean delivery with tubal interruption.  Prior to the procedure, it was confirmed that she desired permanent sterilization.  DESCRIPTION OF PROCEDURE:  The patient was identified and brought to the operating room and placed on the operating table.  A time-out was taken and the patient's identity and planned surgical procedure were confirmed.  After the establishment of adequate regional anesthesia, the patient was placed in the dorsal supine position in left lateral tilt and her abdomen was prepped and draped in the usual sterile manner.  A second time-out was taken and the patient's identity and planned surgical procedure were confirmed; it was confirmed that her antibiotics were being administered and that her pneumatic compression stockings were in place and functioning.   The abdomen was entered in the routine manner through a Pfannenstiel incision.  An incision was made in the skin with a #10 blade and was carried to the fascia.  The fascia was then scored sharply in the midline.  The fascial incision was extended bilaterally with Mayo scissors.  The anterior rectus sheath was dissected with scissors and electrocautery off the rectus abdominis superiorly and inferiorly.  The peritoneum was entered bluntly.  A bladder flap was created.  A transverse incision was made in the lower uterine segment with a scalpel and the incision was extended bilaterally with digital traction.  The amniotic fluid was clear and voluminous.  The above described infant was delivered from the Cephalic presentation with the assistance of a Kiwi vacuum extractor, no pop-offs occurred.  The cord was doubly clamped and cut and the baby was handed to the awaiting pediatrician. A sample of cord and cord blood were obtained for analysis.  The placenta was delivered with gentle traction on the cord, and the uterine cavity was cleared with a clean lap.  The uterus was exteriorized, and the uterine incision was closed in one layer of a running locked suture of 0 Vicryl.    The right fallopian tube was identified by the fimbria, double ligated with 0-chromic suture and the intervening segment excised.  The left fallopian tube was identified by the fimbria, double ligated with 0-chromic suture and the intervening segment excised.    The uterus was replaced in the abdominal cavity.  Adequate hemostasis was confirmed along the uterine incision and in the subfascial area.  The fascia was closed with a single running suture of 0 Vicryl.  The subcutaneous tissue was closed with a running suture of 3-0 Vicryl.  The skin was closed with a running subcuticular closure of 3-0 Monocryl.  Dermabond was applied to the incision.  The vagina was cleared of clots.  A debriefing was held at the end of the procedure; all counts were correct and no outstanding issues were identified.  The patient left for the recovery room in good condition. Monitoring of adequate nutrition using the baby's weight, frequency and duration of feedings, and adequate elimination patterns each day was emphasized and close observation encouraged. The baby's daily feeding record was noted and instructions for utilizing it as a tracking system for progress at home was recommended. The pt's questions were addressed while the risks of supplementing with formula and using pacifiers was discussed. The pt was encouraged to continue demand feedings without time restrictions and supplement only after the baby has completed her feeding.     Plan: Continue to provide lactation support and assistance to help the pt meet her breastfeeding goals. Reinforce cluster feeding as a newborn behavior that increases breast stimulation, increased milk production and typically indicates a growth spurt.   [**NAME**] BSN, CLC

Obstetrics Operative Report   Date of Surgery: [**DATE**]  PREOPERATIVE DIAGNOSIS:  1) Intrauterine pregnancy at 39  Weeks 2) Prior cesarean x 2 3) Obesity, BMI>40  POSTOPERATIVE DIAGNOSIS:  1) Intrauterine pregnancy at 39  Weeks 2) Prior cesarean x 2 3) Obesity, BMI>40 4) Significant adhesive disease  PROCEDURE:  1) Repeat low transverse cesarean section  SURGEON: [**NAME**] ASSISTANT: [**NAME**]  ANESTHESIOLOGIST: [**NAME**] ANESTHESIA ASSISTANT: [**NAME**]  ANESTHESIA: Spinal  EBL: 800 mL  FLUID REPLACEMENT: 3000 mL  URINE OUTPUT: 150 mL  FINDINGS: Normal uterus, tubes and ovaries bilaterally. Thick adhesion band in mid lower uterine segment. Significant scar tissue of fascia to anterior abdominal wall and underlying rectus muscle.  Liveborn infant female weighing 3492 grams with Apgars of 9 and 9.  SPECIMENS TO PATHOLOGY: none  INDICATIONS: [**NAME**] is a 23 y.o. female para 3013 with history of prior cesarean x 2 presented for repeat cesarean delivery as scheduled at 39 weeks gestation. She declined permanent sterilization by tubal interruption.  DESCRIPTION OF THE PROCEDURE: The patient was identified and brought to the operating room and placed on the operating table.  A time-out was taken and the patient's identity and planned surgical procedure were confirmed.  After the establishment of adequate regional anesthesia, the patient was placed in the dorsal supine position in left lateral tilt and her abdomen was prepped and draped in the usual sterile manner.  A second time-out was taken and the patient's identity and planned surgical procedure were confirmed; it was confirmed that her antibiotics were being administered and that her pneumatic compression stockings were in place and functioning.   The abdomen was entered in the routine manner through her prior incision. The incision was taken down to the level of the fascia which was incised in the midline. The incision was extended laterally in either direction over the rectus muscles. The fascia was dissected off the rectus muscle superiorly and then inferiorly as much as we were able but noted to have dense connective tissue scarring in this area. Due to difficulty separating the fascia from the underlying rectus muscle, the fascia unintentionally had a button-hole effect, approximately 5 cm in length which was repaired with several interrupted sutures of 0-vicryl and integrity of the fascia was assured.  The rectus muscle was divided bluntly. The peritoneum was entered in a clear space bluntlyly.  A bladder flap was created in essence by taking down a thick adhesion band from the mid anterior lower uterine segment where pulled up.  A transverse incision was made in the lower uterine segment with a scalpel and the incision was extended bilaterally with the surgeon's fingers.  The amniotic fluid was clear.  The above described infant was delivered from the Cephalic presentation.  The cord was doubly clamped and cut and the baby was handed to the awaiting pediatrician. A sample of cord and cord blood was obtained for analysis.  The placenta was delivered with gentle traction on the cord, and the uterine cavity was cleared with a clean lap.  The uterus was exteriorized, and the uterine incision was closed in 2 layers, the first a running suture of 0-vicryl and the second a running, imbricating suture of 0-vicryl. The hysterotomy on the left side extended down vertically very slightly and closure of the incision was started from the inferior-most aspect on that side with running, locking sutures then continuing on to the remainder of the transverse hysterotomy closure with running, nonlocking suture.  The uterus was replaced in the abdominal cavity.  Adequate hemostasis was confirmed along the uterine incision, posterior to the bladder, and in the subfascial area.  The fascia was closed with two sutures of 0 Vicryl beginning from either end of the incision and meeting in the midportion.  The subcutaneous tissue was irrigated and not reapproximated given small amount of subcutaneous tissue present in this region of her prior scar. Attestation  I saw and evaluated the patient. I reviewed and agree with the findings and plan as documented in the note. I reviewed the patient's history. I discussed this patient with the ARNP/PA. The patient required the following critical interventions: evaluating patient, reviewing labs and imaging, discussing with consulting physicians, critical considerations of the case, discussing with patient and/or patient's family, documenting in chart and management of IV medications and drips. Comments: The patient was BIBA after she states a tree fell on top of her while shopping at a car dealership. She had (+) LOC. A c-collar was placed by ED staff after EMS delivered patient. After intial assessment of the patient's history and exam revealing hematoma on right side of scalp, bruising to right chest wall, abdomen and flank, the patinet was brought back into the trauma bay. A trauma alert was promptly called and OB, orthopedics and trauma surgery presented to bedside.   Patient denied any vaginal bleeding or leakage of fluid.  The patient had a negative FAST exam. She was hemodynamically stable as trauma surg and Ob also evaluated her.The patient had a GCS of 15 and primary complained of right sided rib pain. Her lung sounds were, clear equal and bilateral and I did not hear any wheezing. Pupils were 3mm and equally reactive. There was no hemotympany. No significant gross deformities were noted to arms or legs. The patient complained primarily of right sided rib pain, while in the ED. Her intial Chest XR was negative for any fracture or sign of pneumothorax.   In conjunction with OB and trauma surgery, decision was made not to get an immediate body CT scan given patient never became hypotensive, tachycardic or showed other signs of hemodynamic instability. Do not want to expose a fetus to such excessive amounts of radiation, unless the clinical situation indicates a life threatening abdominal or intrathoracic bleed for either mom/fetus.  At 17:00, I spoke personally to patient, she had GCS of 15 and was asking for something for rib pain, so morphine was ordered for her. Shortly after this, I signed off care of the patient. OB, trauma surgery and oncoming ED team were all aware of patient. The final disposition pends CT head/c-spine results and a full OB and trauma surgery reassment of the patient's response to therapy. If you are using Tylenol (acetaminophen) for pain relief, please limit your total daily dose to 4 grams or less. Obstetrics Operative Report   Date of Surgery: [**DATE**]  PREOPERATIVE DIAGNOSIS:  1) Intrauterine pregnancy at 39 weeks 3 days 2) Prior cesarean x 1, declines trial of labor  POSTOPERATIVE DIAGNOSIS:  1) Intrauterine pregnancy at 39 weeks 3 days 2) Prior cesarean x 1, declines trial of labor  PROCEDURE:  1) Repeat Low transverse cesarean section  SURGEON: [**NAME**] ASSISTANT: [**NAME**]  ANESTHESIOLOGIST: [**NAME**] ANESTHESIA ASSISTANT: [**NAME**]  ANESTHESIA: Spinal  EBL: 600 mL  FLUID REPLACEMENT: 2000 mL  FINDINGS: Normal uterus, tubes and ovaries bilaterally.  Liveborn infant female weighing 3382 grams with Apgars of 8 and 9.  SPECIMENS TO PATHOLOGY: none  INDICATIONS: [**NAME**] is a 22 y.o. female para 1001 with history of prior cesarean x 1 declined tolac and thus presented for scheduled repeat cesarean delivery at 39 weeks gestation. She declined permanent sterilization by tubal interruption.  DESCRIPTION OF THE PROCEDURE: The patient was identified and brought to the operating room and placed on the operating table.  A time-out was taken and the patient's identity and planned surgical procedure were confirmed.  After the establishment of adequate regional anesthesia, the patient was placed in the dorsal supine position in left lateral tilt and her abdomen was prepped and draped in the usual sterile manner.  A second time-out was taken and the patient's identity and planned surgical procedure were confirmed; it was confirmed that her antibiotics were being administered and that her pneumatic compression stockings were in place and functioning.   The abdomen was entered in the routine manner through a pfannenstiel incision. The incision was taken down to the level of the fascia which was incised in the midline. The incision was extended laterally in either direction over the rectus muscles. The fascia was dissected off the rectus muscle superiorly and then inferiorly. The rectus muscle was divided bluntly. The peritoneum was entered in a clear space sharply.  A bladder flap was created.  A transverse incision was made in the lower uterine segment with a scalpel and the incision was extended bilaterally with the surgeon's fingers.  The amniotic fluid was clear.  The above described infant was delivered from the Cephalic presentation.  The cord was doubly clamped and cut and the baby was handed to the awaiting pediatrician. A sample of cord and cord blood was obtained for analysis.  The placenta was delivered with gentle traction on the cord, and the uterine cavity was cleared with a clean lap.  The uterus was exteriorized, and the uterine incision was closed in 2 layers, the first a running suture of 0-vicryl and the second a running, imbricating suture of 0-vicryl.  The uterus was replaced in the abdominal cavity.  Adequate hemostasis was confirmed along the uterine incision, posterior to the bladder, and in the subfascial area.  The fascia was closed with two sutures of 0 Vicryl beginning from either end of the incision and meeting in the midportion.  The subcutaneous tissue was irrigated and re-approximated with a interrupted sutures of 3-0 Vicryl.  The skin was closed with a running subcuticular closure of 3-0 monocryl.  Dermabond was applied to the incision.  The vagina was cleared of clots.  All counts were correct and the patient left for the recovery room in good condition.   Dictated for Dr. [**NAME**]

Obstetrics Operative Report   Name: Ryanne Early  Date of Surgery: [**DATE**]  PREOPERATIVE DIAGNOSIS:  1) Singleton intrauterine pregnancy at 35 weeks 6 days 2) Prior cesarean delivery times four 3) Undesired fertility 4) Low lying anterior placenta, suspected morbidly adherent placenta  POSTOPERATIVE DIAGNOSIS:  1) Singleton intrauterine pregnancy at 35 weeks 6 days, delivered 2) Prior cesarean delivery times four 3) Undesired fertility 4) Low lying anterior placenta  PROCEDURE:  1) Laparotomy 2) Classical cesarean delivery 3) Bilateral tubal interruption 4) Bilateral partial salpingectomy  SURGEON: [**NAME**] ASSISTANT: [**NAME**]  ANESTHESIOLOGIST: [**NAME**] ANESTHESIA ASSISTANT: Bzdega  ANESTHESIA: epidural, spinal, local  EBL: 800 mL  FLUID REPLACEMENT: 3000 mL  FINDINGS: Normal uterus, tubes and ovaries bilaterally. Scant filmy adhesions between bladder and anterior lower uterine segment. No intra-abdominal adhesions. Increased vascularity in anterior uterus both near fundus and in lower uterine segment. Liveborn infant male weighing 2602 grams with Apgars of 8 and 9. Placenta was removed intact with manual traction.  SPECIMENS TO PATHOLOGY:  Bilateral segments of fallopian tube  INDICATIONS: [**NAME**] is a 35 y.o. female para 2214 at 35w6d with history of four prior cesarean deliveries presenting for scheduled repeat cesarean with possible cesarean-hysterectomy. Patient is at increased risk for morbidly adherent placenta given her history and appearance of placenta and uterus on imaging. Patient does not desire future fertility given risks of multiple cesarean deliveries and associated morbidity and mortality.  DESCRIPTION OF THE PROCEDURE: The patient was identified and brought to the operating room and placed on the operating table. A time-out was taken and the patient's identity and planned surgical procedure were confirmed. After the establishment of adequate regional anesthesia, the patient was placed in the dorsal supine position in left lateral tilt and her abdomen was prepped and draped in the usual sterile manner. A foley catheter was inserted and remained in place during the procedure. A second time-out was taken and the patient's identity and planned surgical procedure were confirmed; it was confirmed that her antibiotics were being administered and that her pneumatic compression stockings were in place and functioning.   The abdomen was entered through a midline vertical incision. The incision was taken down to the level of the fascia which was incised in the midline. The incision was extended inferiorly and superiorly over the rectus muscles. The rectus muscle was divided sharply. The peritoneum was entered in a clear space sharply. A bladder flap was attempted but abandoned due to increased vascularity of the uterus. A classical (vertical) incision was made in the uterine fundus anteriorly with a scalpel and the incision was extended slightly with manual traction. The amniotic fluid was scant but clear. The above described infant was in cephalic position, but due to the superior location of the hysterotomy the infant was delivered from the breech presentation. The cord was doubly clamped and cut and the baby was handed to the awaiting pediatrician. A sample of cord and cord blood was obtained for analysis.  The hysterotomy edges were clamped with ring forceps. The hysterotomy edges were secured with a running locked suture of 0 Chromic. The placenta was delivered with gentle traction on the umbilical cord, and the placenta was closely inspected and noted to be intact. There was minimal bleeding from the uterus at this point. The hysterotomy was closed in a single layer with a running suture of 0 Chromic.    The left fallopian tube was identified to its fimbriated end and a defect was made in a relatively avascular portion of the mesosalpinx underlying the mid isthmic portion of the tube. A segment of the mid isthmic portion of the tube was ligated with two sutures of 0 Chromic suture and the intervening portion of the tube excised and handed off the field; adequate hemostasis was assured. The exact same procedure was performed on the opposite side after identifying that tube to its fimbriated end; again, adequate hemostasis was assured. Patient expressed desire for salpingectomy to reduce risk of fallopian tube carcinoma so the fimbriated ends of the fallopian tubes were excised with handheld Ligasure device. The fimbriated ends of fallopian tube were handed off the field to be labeled and sent to Pathology.  Adequate hemostasis was confirmed along the uterine incision, in the adnexa, posterior to the bladder, and in the subfascial area. The fascia was closed with two sutures of 0 Vicryl beginning from either end of the incision and meeting in the midportion. The subcutaneous tissue was irrigated and re-approximated with a running suture and interrupted sutures of 3-0 Vicryl. The skin was closed with a running subcuticular closure of 3-0 Monocryl. Dermabond mesh tape (Prineo) was applied to the incision. The vagina was cleared of clots. All counts were correct and the patient left for the recovery room in good condition.  [**NAME**], MD [**DATE**]

SPECIMENS TO PATHOLOGY:  Segments from each tube  INDICATIONS: [**NAME**] is a 25 y.o. female para 3225 who requests sterilization.  Patient understands this is a permanent procedure.  DESCRIPTION OF THE PROCEDURE:   The patient was identified and brought to the operating room and placed on the operating table.  A time-out was taken and the patient's identity and planned surgical procedure were confirmed.  After the establishment of adequate regional anesthesia, the patient was placed in the dorsal supine position and her abdomen was prepped and draped in the usual sterile manner.  A second time-out was taken and the patient's identity and planned surgical procedure were confirmed.  The abdominal cavity was entered through a small, transverse infraumbilical incision.  The left fallopian tube was identified to its fimbriated end and a defect was made in a relatively avascular portion of the mesosalpinx underlying the mid isthmic portion of the tube.  A segment of the mid isthmic portion of the tube was ligated with two sutures of 0 Chromic suture and the intervening portion of the tube was excised and handed off the field; adequate hemostasis was assured.  The exact same procedure was performed on the opposite side after identifying that tube to its fimbriated end; again, adequate hemostasis was assured.  The fascia was closed with a running suture of 0 Vicryl.  The subcutaneous tissue was reapproximated with 0 vicryl.  The skin incision was closed with a running subcuticular suture of monocryl.  The patient was transferred to the recovery room in stable condition.  All counts were correct at the end of the procedure.  [**NAME**], MD OB/GYN PGY1

SURGICAL SUMMARY  Preoperative diagnosis: 39 weeks fetal arthrogryposis (thought all extremities involved)  Postoperative Diagnosis: same  Operation Performed: primary LUT cesarean section  Surgeon: [**NAME**]/[**NAME**]    Assistant: deatsman  Anesthesiologist: euliano    Assistant: [**NAME**]  Anesthesia: spinal  Pathology: none   Blood and Fluids: EBL: 800ml   IVF:1500ml Urine: 150 ml and clear   DESCRIPTION OF SURGERY  Quality and Safety Measures: 1) The patient was properly identified.  2) A time out was performed    3) Prophylactic antibiotics were provided (see anesthesia record) 4) Sequential compression stockings were in place and functioning. 5) A lower body warmer was in place and functioning. 6) At the conclusion of the case all counts were correct  7) Pacemaker was interrogated before the case, a  magnet was present to stop the generator if needed.  Surgical Aspects: Entry: Skin incision was pfannenstiel. Adhesive disease was not encountered. A bladder flap was created. A primary LUT incision was made on the lower uterine segment.     Closure: The uterus was closed in a double layer fashion with vicryl suture.  The bladder flap was closed.   The peritoneum was closed.  The fascia was closed with 0-Vicryl starting at each corner and working medial to the midline.  The subcutaneous layer was reapproximated with 3-0 vicryl.     A subcuticular closure of the skin was performed using 3-0 monocryl.  FETUS/NEONATE  Amniotic fluid was clear.   Liveborn infant female  Birthweight: 2448 grams. Apgars of 8 and [**DATE**].  The fetus was delivered from the Cephalic presentation.   The cord was clamped and cut and the baby handed to the pediatric team.  A segment of umbilical cord was provided for cord blood gases.  Cord Gases:(Arterial)    HEMORRHAGE RISK   The placenta was not adherent and delivered without difficulty.  There was no uterine atony. There were no unusual extensions.  All tissue planes were inspected for bleeding and were noted to be dry.  No transfusion was required.   PATIENT DISPOSITION The patient left for the recovery room in good condition. Date of Surgery: [**DATE**]  PREOPERATIVE DIAGNOSIS:  1) Intrauterine pregnancy at 40 weeks 2) Arrest of dilation 3) Non reassuring fetal heart rate tracing 4) Prior c/s x 1  POSTOPERATIVE DIAGNOSIS:  1) Intrauterine pregnancy at 40 weeks 2) Arrest of dilation 3) Non reassuring fetal heart rate tracing 4) Prior c/s x 1 5) TOLAC  PROCEDURE:  1) Low transverse cesarean section  SURGEON: [**NAME**] ASSISTANT: [**NAME**]  ANESTHESIOLOGIST: [**NAME**] ANESTHESIA ASSISTANT: Sams  ANESTHESIA: Epidural  EBL: 800 mL  FLUID REPLACEMENT: 800 mL  FINDINGS: Normal uterus, tubes and ovaries bilaterally.  Liveborn infant male weighing 2864 grams with Apgars of 8 and 9. The patient underwent induction of labor with foley bulb, pitocin, and AROM and remained at 4 cm cervical dilation for 24 hours. During this time the FHT demonstrated minimal variability with intermittent late appearing decelerations. The decision was made to proceed with a repeat cesarean section.  SPECIMENS TO PATHOLOGY: None  INDICATIONS: [**NAME**] is a 23 y.o. female para 2012 at 40w4d GA who was admitted for scheduled induction of labor in the setting or a prior cesarean section.   DESCRIPTION OF THE PROCEDURE: The patient was identified and brought to the operating room and placed on the operating table.  A time-out was taken and the patient's identity and planned surgical procedure were confirmed.  After the establishment of adequate regional anesthesia, the patient was placed in the dorsal supine position in left lateral tilt and her abdomen was prepped and draped in the usual sterile manner.  A second time-out was taken and the patient's identity and planned surgical procedure were confirmed; it was confirmed that her antibiotics were being administered and that her pneumatic compression stockings were in place and functioning.   The abdomen was entered in the routine manner through a Pfannenstiel incision.  The subcutaneous tissue was incised with the scalpel. The fascia was scored with the scalpel. The fascial incision was extended bilaterally with curved mayo scissors. The fascia was dissected away from the rectus muscle with blunt dissection, electrocautery, and curved mayo scissors. The rectus muscle was divided at the midline and then laterally on the left. The left lateral division was made due to very thickened peritoneum located at the midline. The peritoneum was entered with Metzenbaum scissors at the left lateral division of the rectus muscle. The rectus muscle and the peritoneum was divided toward the midline with electrocautery. The peritoneal incision was then extended with gentle traction. A bladder flap was created.  A transverse incision was made in the lower uterine segment with a scalpel and the incision was extended with traction. The hysterotomy was extended superiorly at bilateral angles.  The amniotic fluid was clear.  The above described infant was delivered from the Cephalic presentation.  The cord was doubly clamped and cut and the baby was handed to the awaiting pediatrician. A sample of cord and cord blood were obtained for analysis.  The placenta was delivered with gentle traction on the cord, and the uterine cavity was cleared with a clean lap.  The uterus was exteriorized, and the uterine incision was closed in a single layer, a running locking suture of 0-Monocryl.   The uterus was replaced in the abdominal cavity.  Adequate hemostasis was confirmed along the uterine incision and in the subfascial area.  The fascia was closed with a single running suture of 0 Vicryl.  The subcutaneous tissue was closed with two layers of running suture of 3-0 Vicryl.  The skin was closed with a running subcuticular closure of 3-0 Monocryl.  Dermabond was applied to the incision.  The vagina was cleared of clots.  All counts were correct and the patient left for the recovery room in good condition.  Complications: none  [**NAME**] M.D.  I was present for the entire case. Date of Surgery: [**DATE**]  PREOPERATIVE DIAGNOSIS:  1) Intrauterine pregnancy at 24 weeks 2) Dichorionic diamniotic twins 3) Premature preterm rupture of membranes of Twin A at 21 weeks 4) Fetal malpresentation 5) Preterm labor 6) Suspected chorioamnionitis  POSTOPERATIVE DIAGNOSIS:  1) Intrauterine pregnancy at 24 weeks 2) Dichorionic diamniotic twins 3) Premature preterm rupture of membranes of Twin A at 21 weeks 4) Fetal malpresentation 5) Preterm labor 6) Suspected chorioamnionitis 7) Delivered  PROCEDURE:  1) Primary classical cesarean section   SURGEON: [**NAME**] ASSISTANTS: [**NAME**]  ANESTHESIOLOGIST: [**NAME**] ANESTHESIA ASSISTANT: [**NAME**]  ANESTHESIA: Spinal  EBL: 1000 mL  FLUID REPLACEMENT: 2200 mL  FINDINGS: Normal uterus, tubes and ovaries bilaterally.  Baby A (intact): Liveborn infant male weighing 680 grams with Apgars of 6 and 8. Baby B (PPROM): Liveborn infant male weighing 570 grams with Apgars of 6 and 6.   SPECIMENS TO PATHOLOGY: Placenta  INDICATIONS: 25 y.o. para 0 at 24w0d admitted with dichorionic diamniotic twins due to premature preterm rupture of membranes of twin A at 21 weeks. She received a betamethasone course at 23w4d and was given antibiotics for latency. At 24w0d, she began having painful contractions. On sterile speculum exam, she was dilated to 4cm and she had milky discharge. She had a temperature of 37.9C with fetal tachycardia and therefore chorioamnionitis was suspected. She progressed to 6cm dilation and was therefore taken to the operating room for cesarean delivery.   DESCRIPTION OF THE PROCEDURE: The patient was identified and brought to the operating room and placed on the operating table.  A time-out was taken and the patient's identity and planned surgical procedure were confirmed.  After the establishment of adequate regional anesthesia, the patient was placed in the dorsal supine position in left lateral tilt and her abdomen was prepped and draped in the usual sterile manner.  A second time-out was taken and the patient's identity and planned surgical procedure were confirmed; it was confirmed that her antibiotics were being administered and that her pneumatic compression stockings were in place and functioning.   The abdomen was entered in the routine manner through a Pfannenstiel incision.  A bladder flap was not created.  A classical incision was made in the uterus segment with a scalpel and the incision was extended superiorly with bandage scissors. The amniotic fluid surrounding the non-presenting twin was clear and ruptured with an Allis clamp. The previously described twin B was delivered first from the breech presentation and will now be called twin A.  The second twin (PPROM) was also delivered from breech presentation. The cords were doubly clamped and cut, and the babies were handed to the awaiting pediatricians. A sample of cord and cord blood were obtained for analysis.  The placenta was delivered with gentle traction on the cord, and the uterine cavity was cleared with a clean lap.  The uterus was exteriorized, and the uterus was closed in 4 layers, first a running stitch of 0 Vicryl, then a running imbricating layer of 0 Vicryl. The 3rd layer was created using a series of horizontal mattress sutures of 0 Vicryl just under the serosal layer. The final layer was a baseball stitch using 2-0 Vicryl. The uterus was replaced in the abdominal cavity.  The fascia was closed with a suture of 0 Vicryl.  The subcutaneous tissue was irrigated with saline.  The subcutaneous tissue was approximated with a running suture of 2-0 vicryl.  The skin was closed with a subcuticular stitch of 3-0 monocryl.  Dermabond was applied to the incision.  The vagina was cleared of clots.  All counts were correct and the patient left for the recovery room in good condition.  [**NAME**], MD

SPECIMENS TO PATHOLOGY: None  INDICATIONS: [**NAME**] is a 26yo P0020 who was admitted at 39 weeks gestation with severely elevated blood pressures indicative of pre-eclampsia with severe features. On arrival, she had a category 2 fetal heart tracing. She was admitted and started on magnesium therapy and prior to starting pitocin induction of labor, she began contracting every 4-5 minutes. She then began having deep variable decelerations that could not be resolved with intrauterine resuscitation and was therefore taken to the operating room for Stat cesarean delivery.  DESCRIPTION OF THE PROCEDURE: The patient was identified and brought to the operating room and placed on the operating table. A time-out was taken and the patient's identity and planned surgical procedure were confirmed. After the establishment of adequate regional anesthesia, the patient was placed in the dorsal supine position in left lateral tilt and her abdomen was prepped and draped in the usual sterile manner. A second time-out was taken and the patient's identity and planned surgical procedure were confirmed; it was confirmed that her antibiotics were being administered and that her pneumatic compression stockings were in place and functioning.  The abdomen was entered in the routine manner through a Pfanenstiel incision. The fascia was scored in the midline and extended with sharp dissection laterally. The underlying rectus muscle was dissected off the fascia with blunt dissection. The rectus muscles were separated in the midline with blunt dissection and the peritoneum was entered bluntly. A bladder flap was not created. A low transverse incision was made in the lower uterine segment with a scalpel and the incision was extended bilaterally with traction. The amniotic fluid was meconium stained. The above described infant was delivered from the Cephalic presentation with the assistance of a Kiwi vacuum. There were no pop offs. The cord was doubly clamped and cut and the baby was handed to the awaiting pediatrician. A sample of cord and cord blood were obtained for analysis. Cord blood for donation was collected. The placenta was delivered with gentle traction on the cord, and the uterine cavity was cleared with a clean lap. The uterus was exteriorized, and the uterine incision was closed in two layers, the first a running suture of 0 Monocryl and the second a running, imbricating suture of 0 Monocryl.  The uterus was replaced in the abdominal cavity. Adequate hemostasis was confirmed along the uterine incision and in the subfascial area. The fascia was closed with a single running suture of 0 Vicryl. The subcutaneous fat was closed with a running suture of 3-0 Vicryl. The skin was closed with a running subcuticular closure of 3-0 Monocryl. Dermabond was applied to the incision. The vagina was cleared of clots. All counts were correct and the patient left for the recovery room in good condition.   [**NAME**], MD

Department of Obstetrics & Gynecology  Operative Note   Date of Surgery: [**DATE**]  PREOPERATIVE DIAGNOSIS:  1) Intrauterine pregnancy at 37w0d  2) History of prior cesarean x2 3) History of uterine window  4) Gestational thrombocytopenia  5) Suspected fetal mesenteric cyst  6) Undesired fertility  7) Non-reassuring fetal heart tracing following placement of spinal anesthesia   POSTOPERATIVE DIAGNOSIS:  1) Intrauterine pregnancy at 37w0d  2) History of prior cesarean x2 3) History of uterine window  4) Gestational thrombocytopenia  5) Suspected fetal mesenteric cyst  6) Undesired fertility  7) Non-reassuring fetal heart tracing following placement of spinal anesthesia  8) Delivered   PROCEDURE:  1) Low transverse cesarean section 2) Parkland postpartum bilateral tubal interruption  SURGEON: Dr. [**NAME**]  ASSISTANT: Dr. [**NAME**]   ANESTHESIOLOGIST: Dr. [**NAME**]  ANESTHESIA ASSISTANT: Dr. [**NAME**]   ANESTHESIA: Spinal   EBL: 700 mL  FLUID REPLACEMENT: 2000 mL  FINDINGS: Minimal adhesions noted within abdomen.  Normal uterus, tubes and ovaries bilaterally.  Liveborn infant male weighing 3158 grams with Apgars of 7 and 9.  CORD GASES: (Areterial)  Lab Results  Component Value Date   PHCORDA 7.27 [**DATE**]      (Venous):  Lab Results  Component Value Date   PHCORDV 7.33 [**DATE**]     SPECIMENS TO PATHOLOGY:  Segments from each tube  INDICATIONS: [**NAME**] is a 31 y.o. female P2113, with history of prior cesarean x2, history of uterine window noted during last cesarean, and suspected fetal mesenteric cyst who presented at 37w0d for her scheduled repeat cesarean and BTI, as she desired no future fertility. After placement of spinal anesthesia, fetal bradycardia to the 60s was noted. Decision was made to proceed with emergent cesarean delivery.   DESCRIPTION OF THE PROCEDURE: The patient was identified and brought to the operating room and placed on the operating table.  A time-out was taken and the patient's identity and planned surgical procedure were confirmed.  After the establishment of adequate regional anesthesia, the patient was placed in the dorsal supine position in left lateral tilt. Fetal bradycardia was noted. An emergent cesarean section was called. Her abdomen was prepped and draped in the usual sterile manner.  A second time-out was taken and the patient's identity and planned surgical procedure were confirmed; it was confirmed that her antibiotics were being administered and that her pneumatic compression stockings were in place and functioning.   The abdomen was entered in the routine manner through prior Pfanenstiel incision.  The incision was taken down to the level of the fascia which was incised in the midline with scalpel. The incision was extended laterally in either direction over the rectus muscles.  The rectus muscle was divided sharply with a scalpel. The peritoneum was entered bluntly.  A transverse incision was made in the lower uterine segment with a scalpel and the incision was extended bilaterally with the surgeon's fingers.  The amniotic fluid was clear upon rupture.  The above described infant was delivered from the Cephalic presentation.  The cord was doubly clamped and cut and the baby was handed to the awaiting pediatrician. A sample of cord and cord blood was obtained for analysis.  The placenta was delivered with gentle traction on the cord, and the uterine cavity was cleared with a clean lap.  The uterus was exteriorized, and the uterine incision was closed in  a running suture of 0 Vicryl. Additional sutures of 0 Vicryl were placed along hysterotomy for additional hemostasis.   The right fallopian tube was identified to its fimbriated end and a defect was made in a relatively avascular portion of the mesosalpinx underlying the mid isthmic portion of the tube.  A segment of the mid isthmic portion of the tube was ligated with two sutures of 0 Chromic suture and the intervening portion of the tube excised and handed off the field; adequate hemostasis was assured.  The exact same procedure was performed on the opposite side after identifying that tube to its fimbriated end; again, adequate hemostasis was assured.  The uterus was replaced in the abdominal cavity.  Adequate hemostasis was confirmed along the uterine incision, posterior to the bladder, and in the subfascial area.  The fascia was closed with one suture of 0 Vicryl.  The subcutaneous tissue was irrigated and closed with running suture of 3-0 vicryl.  The skin was closed with a running subcuticular closure of 3-0 Monocryl.  Dermabond was applied to the incision.  The vagina was cleared of clots.  All counts were correct and the patient left for the recovery room in good condition.  Dictated for Dr. [**NAME**], MD

Date of Surgery: [**DATE**]  PREOPERATIVE DIAGNOSIS:  1) Intrauterine pregnancy at 33 weeks 2) Pre-eclampsia 3) Fetal intrauterine growth restriction 4) Oligohydramnios 5) Non-reassuring fetal heart tracing  POSTOPERATIVE DIAGNOSIS:  1) Intrauterine pregnancy at 33 weeks 2) Pre-eclampsia 3) Fetal intrauterine growth restriction 4) Oligohydramnios 5) Non-reassuring fetal heart tracing 6) Suspected placental abruption  PROCEDURE:  1) Primary low transverse cesarean section  SURGEON: [**NAME**] ASSISTANTS: [**NAME**]  ANESTHESIOLOGIST: [**NAME**] ANESTHESIA ASSISTANT: [**NAME**]  ANESTHESIA: Spinal  EBL: 800 mL  FLUID REPLACEMENT: 1500 mL  FINDINGS: Normal uterus, tubes and ovaries bilaterally. Liveborn infant female weighing 2438 grams with Apgars of 8 and 9. Very scant clear amniotic fluid. Placenta appeared to have approximately 20% abruption along the margin.   SPECIMENS TO PATHOLOGY: Placenta  INDICATIONS: 29 y.o. para 0111 at 33w5d admitted with pre-eclampsia, oligohydramnios and intrauterine growth restriction. On daily nonstress test, she was found to have repetitive prolonged variable and late decelerations not responsive to intrauterine resuscitation and was therefore taken to the operating room for cesarean delivery.   DESCRIPTION OF THE PROCEDURE: The patient was identified and brought to the operating room and placed on the operating table.  A time-out was taken and the patient's identity and planned surgical procedure were confirmed.  After the establishment of adequate regional anesthesia, the patient was placed in the dorsal supine position in left lateral tilt and her abdomen was prepped and draped in the usual sterile manner.  A second time-out was taken and the patient's identity and planned surgical procedure were confirmed; it was confirmed that her antibiotics were being administered and that her pneumatic compression stockings were in place and functioning.   The abdomen was entered in the routine manner through a Pfannenstiel incision.  A bladder flap was not created.  A transverse incision was made in the lower uterine segment with a scalpel and the incision was extended bilaterally with tractiong.  The amniotic fluid was very scant but clear.  The above described infant was delivered from the Cephalic presentation.  The cord was doubly clamped and cut, and the baby was handed to the awaiting pediatricians. A sample of cord and cord blood were obtained for analysis.  The placenta was delivered with gentle traction on the cord, and the uterine cavity was cleared with a clean lap.  The uterus was exteriorized, and closed in 2 layers, the first a running suture of 0 Vicryl and the second a running, imbricating suture of 0 Vicryl.  The uterus was replaced in the abdominal cavity.  The fascia was closed with a suture of 0 Vicryl.  The subcutaneous tissue was irrigated with saline.  The subcutaneous tissue was approximated with a running suture of 3-0 vicryl.  The skin was closed with a subcuticular stitch of 3-0 monocryl.  Dermabond was applied to the incision.  The vagina was cleared of clots.  All counts were correct and the patient left for the recovery room in good condition.   [**NAME**], MD

Pt reports much less discomfort with deeper latch.  Discussed importance of asymmetrical, chin-led latch, as well as allowing infant to determine feeding times by observing infant for feeding cues. Encouraged to choose a position that provides upper back support and guidance.  Instructed to allow infant to finish on one breast, using breast compressions to maximize feeding time before switching to second breast at each feeding.  Reviewed nipple care, typical cluster feeding behavior, infant stomach capacity and expected output for infant.  Also discussed managing possible milk oversupply during milk onset. Discouraged use of pacifiers or artificial nipples until breastfeeding is well-established, around 3-4 weeks of age. Encouraged maximizing skin to skin time with infant over the next several days as well.  Pt provided with a copy of the [**LOCATION_INSTITUTE**] Breastfeeding book and made aware of resources available to her after discharge.  Pt plans to return to work after 12 weeks. Has already obtained a pump and reviewed recommended milk storage guidelines. Invited to support group.   Plan: Will continue to support pt's breastfeeding goals. Encouraged her to call for assistance as needed, and left contact information. Pt verbalized understanding.

Date of Surgery: [**DATE**]  PREOPERATIVE DIAGNOSIS:  1) Intrauterine pregnancy at 39 weeks 2) Prior cesarean x 1 3) Fetal transposition of the great arteries  POSTOPERATIVE DIAGNOSIS:  1) Intrauterine pregnancy at 39 weeks 2) Prior cesarean x 1 3) Fetal transposition of the great arteries  PROCEDURE:  1) Repeat low transverse cesarean section  SURGEON: Oguneleye ASSISTANTS: [**NAME**]  ANESTHESIOLOGIST: [**NAME**] ANESTHESIA ASSISTANT: [**NAME**]  ANESTHESIA: Spinal  EBL: 1000 mL  FLUID REPLACEMENT: 1500 mL  FINDINGS: Severe pelvic adhesive disease between the anterior body of the uterus and the anterior abdominal wall. Severe adhesions also between the lower uterine segment to the bladder. Thick band of adhesion at the uterine fundus that precluded exteriorization. Normal uterus, tubes and ovaries bilaterally.  Liveborn infant male weighing 3864 grams with Apgars of 7 and 9.  SPECIMENS TO PATHOLOGY: None  INDICATIONS: 26 y.o. para 1001 at 39w1d admitted for scheduled repeat cesarean delivery. This pregnancy is complicated by fetal transposition of the great arteries. She has had a prior cesarean delivery and declines trial of labor.   DESCRIPTION OF THE PROCEDURE: The patient was identified and brought to the operating room and placed on the operating table.  A time-out was taken and the patient's identity and planned surgical procedure were confirmed.  After the establishment of adequate regional anesthesia, the patient was placed in the dorsal supine position in left lateral tilt and her abdomen was prepped and draped in the usual sterile manner.  A second time-out was taken and the patient's identity and planned surgical procedure were confirmed; it was confirmed that her antibiotics were being administered and that her pneumatic compression stockings were in place and functioning.   The abdomen was entered in the routine manner through a Pfannenstiel incision. Severe adhesive disease was encountered. A bladder flap was not created.  A transverse incision was made in the lower uterine segment with a scalpel and the incision was extended bilaterally with traction.  The amniotic fluid was clear.  The left rectus muscle was cut with bandage scissors to allow for delivery of the fetal head. The above described infant was delivered from the Cephalic presentation.  The cord was doubly clamped and cut, and the baby was handed to the awaiting pediatricians. A sample of cord and cord blood were obtained for analysis.  The placenta was delivered with gentle traction on the cord, and the uterine cavity was cleared with a clean lap.  The uterus was NOT exteriorized due to severe adhesions. The corner of the uterine incision was closed with a figure of 8 with 0-monocryl and the uterus was closed in 2 layers, the first a running suture of 0 monocryl and the second a running suture of 0 monocryl. The uterine incision was examined closely and was hemostatic.  The fascia was closed with a suture of 0 Vicryl.  The subcutaneous tissue was irrigated with saline.  The subcutaneous tissue was approximated with interrupted sutures of 3-0 chormic.  The skin was closed with a subcuticular stitch of 4-0 monocryl.  Dermabond was applied to the incision.  The vagina was cleared of clots.  All counts were correct and the patient left for the recovery room in good condition.  [**NAME**], MD

Attending note.  I met with the patient and her partner together with Drs. Egerman from MFM, Dr. [**NAME**] from neonatology, and Dr. [**NAME**] to discuss a plan of care.  Briefly, Ms. [**NAME**] is a 27 yo P2002 at 25 4/7 wks who has been followed by HROB and peds cardiology since approximately 20 weeks gestation at which time she was diagnosed with fetal non-immune hydrops.  Infectious disease workup and fetal ECHO did not reveal underlying etiology.  Pregnancy o/w complicated by CHTN on aldomet and procardia.  She presented today for follow-up outpatient fetal ECHO which showed significantly worsening fetal hydrops.  She was then directly admitted for fetal monitoring and a betamethasone course and evaluation of elevated BPs with concern for possible mirror syndrome.    On admission, initial BPs noted to be 130's-170's/90's-110's.  No s/s preE.  Pt had not taken her anti-HTN meds today, and was given labetalol 20mg IV x 1 dose with subsequent BPs noted to be 120-130's/80-90's.  PreE panel shows nl plts,LFTs and Cr.  Pr/Cr ratio = 361.  Pt is currently receiving magnesium sulfate for sz prophylaxis and has received her 1st dose of betamethasone at 1640.  FHT currently shows decreased variability with repetitive variable decelerations.  Together we again discussed the poor fetal prognosis with likely in-utero fetal demise if the pregnancy continues.  The patient is also aware that there is low chance of fetal survival with delivery at this GA.  The chance of survival cannot be well-predicted without knowing how much functional lung tissue is present.  The patient was offered comfort measures for the baby if the baby is delivered and the neonatologists feel that invasive intervention would be futile.  The patient requests full intervention for the baby if delivery is recommended at this time.  In making a decision for delivery to try to maximize fetal survival, the decision is based on whether or not we can try to get a full course of betamethasone administered prior to complete fetal deterioration vs. whether or not delaying delivery would lead to a stat C/S under GA in the setting of fetal bradycardia which would likely further diminish chances of fetal survival in this already compromised baby.  We have discussed with the patient that our recommendation is to proceed with cesarean delivery now due to FHR concerns.  I also again addressed the patient's previous desire to have permanent sterilization.  We again discussed the risk of regret, and the patient has decided to opt for a non-permanent method of birth control until she can give further consideration to permanent sterilization.  Currently preparing to transfer pt to OR for C/S.  Anesthesia aware.  [**NAME**], MD Assistant Professor Department of Obstetrics and Gynecology [**LOCATION_INSTITUTE**]

SPECIMENS TO PATHOLOGY: placenta  INDICATIONS: [**NAME**] is a 34 y.o. female now P2002 s/p repeat cesarean section for NRFHT, arrest of descent and chorioamnionitis.  DESCRIPTION OF THE PROCEDURE: The patient was identified and brought to the operating room and placed on the operating table.  A time-out was taken and the patient's identity and planned surgical procedure were confirmed.  After the establishment of adequate regional anesthesia, the patient was placed in the dorsal supine position in left lateral tilt and her abdomen was prepped and draped in the usual sterile manner.  A second time-out was taken and the patient's identity and planned surgical procedure were confirmed; it was confirmed that her antibiotics were being administered and that her pneumatic compression stockings were in place and functioning.   The abdomen was entered in the routine manner through a Pfannenstiel incision.  A bladder flap was created.  A transverse incision was made in the lower uterine segment with a scalpel and the incision was extended bilaterally with cephalo-caudal traction.  The amniotic fluid was meconium stained.  The above described infant was delivered from the Cephalic presentation.  The cord was doubly clamped and cut and the baby was handed to the awaiting pediatrician. A sample of cord and cord blood were obtained for analysis.  The placenta was delivered with gentle traction on the cord, and the uterine cavity was cleared with a clean lap.  The uterus was exteriorized, and the uterine incision was closed in two layers: the first layer was 2 running sutures of 0 Vicryl and the second layer a partial imbricating suture of 2-0 Vicryl.    The uterus was replaced in the abdominal cavity.  Adequate hemostasis was confirmed along the uterine incision and in the subfascial area.  The fascia was closed with a single running suture of 0 Vicryl.  The subcutaneous tissue was closed with interrupted sutures of 0-chromic. The skin was closed with a running subcuticular closure of 3-0 Monocryl.  Dermabond was applied to the incision.  The vagina was cleared of clots.  All counts were correct and the patient left for the recovery room in good condition.     [**NAME**], MD  Attending Note: I was present for the entire procedure.  I have reviewed and agree with the resident documentation in the note above.     [**NAME**], MD

S  Procedure: After satisfactory anesthesia, the patient was prepped and draped in a routine fashion for abdominal surgery.  Time-out confirmed patient and procedure.  The abdomen was entered with a Pfannensteil approach.  A bladder flap was created and then a transverse incision was made in the lower uterine segment with a scalpel and extended laterally with the surgeons fingers.  Amniotic fluid was clear.  The above described infant was delivered from the Cephalic, Breech presentation.  The cord was clamped and cut and the baby handed to the pediatrician.  Blood for gases and DNA was obtained.  The placenta was delivered with cord traction.  The uterus was wiped out with a lap.  The uterus was closed in a double layer closure using 0-vicryl.  The fascia was closed with 1 suture/s of 0-Vicryl starting at the angle and running in a continuous fashion. The subcutaneous tissue was irrigated.  The skin was closed with 3-0 monocryl.  Dermabond was applied.  The vagina was cleared of clots.  All counts were correct and the patient left for the recovery room in good condition.   [**NAME**]  Dictated for Dr. [**NAME**]

Assessment: Pt feels breastfeeding has been difficult at times, is concerned with infant weight loss now as 11% below birth weight. She has very little confidence in her ability to latch infant well.  Infant is currently latched and nursing in cradle position on left breast - nipple-only latch noted, chin away from breast, torso facing ceiling.  Pt states her nipples are very sore. Breasts are soft, round, filling.  Nipples are everted, bilateral abrasions c/w ineffective latch.  Pt was taught how to hand express her breasts, and multiple drops of colostrum noted bilaterally. States she was unable to BF her other children for very long, admits she had very little support.  Determined to nurse this infant for at least 6 months. Infant EBF at this time.  Intervention: Assisted pt to reposition and latch infant in clutch hold on left breast with deep asymmetrical latch and rhythmic suck/ audible swallow.  Pt reports much less discomfort with latch, very pleased.  Discussed importance of asymmetrical, chin-led latch, as well as allowing infant to determine feeding times by observing infant for feeding cues.  Instructed to allow infant to finish on one breast, using breast compressions to maximize feeding time before switching to second breast at each feeding.  Reviewed nipple care, typical cluster feeding behavior, infant stomach capacity and expected output for infant. Discouraged use of pacifiers or artificial nipples until breastfeeding is well-established, around 3-4 weeks of age. Encouraged maximizing skin to skin time with infant over the next several days as well.  Pt was able to unlatch/ relatch infant x2 during visit, gaining confidence.  Pt provided with a copy of the [**LOCATION_INSTITUTE**] Breastfeeding book and made aware of resources available to her after discharge.  Pt plans to return to work most likely after 12 weeks. Discussed obtaining a pump and reviewed recommended milk storage guidelines.   Plan: Will continue to support pt's breastfeeding goals. Encouraged her to call for assistance as needed, and left contact information. Pt verbalized understanding.
