SPECIMENS TO PATHOLOGY:  INDICATIONS: [**NAME**] is a 29 y.o. female para 4125 who was admitted to labor and delivery at 35 weeks for chest pain and then extended monitoring after falling and hitting her abdomen. The pt's tocometry showed uterine irritability and the pt complained of abdominal pain, but this subsided and FHT was reactive over the course of the evening.  At 0615, the pt returned from using the restroom and nursing was unable to obtain a fetal heart tone. A heart beat could not be seen on ultrasound but fetal movement was noted. The pt was moved to the OR and a normal heart rate was found on repeat ultrasound. It was felt the fetus likely had an episode of bradycardia. Given bradycardia in the setting of recent fall, abdominal pain, and uterine irritability, we proceeded with cesarean delivery.  DESCRIPTION OF THE PROCEDURE: The patient was identified and brought to the operating room and placed on the operating table.  After the establishment of adequate regional anesthesia, the patient was placed in the dorsal supine position in left lateral tilt and her abdomen was prepped and draped in the usual sterile manner.   The abdomen was entered in the routine manner through a pfannensteil incision.  A bladder flap was created bluntly.  A transverse incision was made in the lower uterine segment with a scalpel and the incision was extended bilaterally with the surgeon's fingers.  The amniotic fluid was clear.  The above described infant was delivered from the Breech presentation.  The cord was doubly clamped and cut and the baby was handed to the awaiting pediatrician. A sample of cord and cord blood was obtained for analysis.  The placenta was delivered with gentle traction on the cord, and the uterine cavity was cleared with a clean lap.  The uterus was exteriorized, and the uterine incision was closed in 2 layers, the first a running locking suture of 0 Vicryl and the second a running, imbricating suture of 0 Vicryl.  Excellent hemostasis was noted.   Next attention was turned to the tubal ligation. The right fallopian tube was identified by the fimbria, double ligated with #1-plain gut suture and the intervening segment excised.  The left fallopian tube was identified by the fimbria, double ligated with #1 plain gut suture and the intervening segment excised.    It was noted after removing the segment of the left tube, that there was a small defect in the uterine serosa between the round ligament and fallopian tube. This was oversewn with a 3-0 vicryl.    The uterus was replaced in the abdominal cavity.  Adequate hemostasis was confirmed along the uterine incision. However on re-examination of the left fallopian tube and left infundipular pelvic ligament, the distal portion of the fallopian tube was noted to be forming a large hematoma as was the IP. The uterus was exteriorized. The distal portion of the fallopian tube was removed by progressively clamping, cutting, and tying along the fallopian tube/mesosalping junction. After removal of the tube. The left side of the uterus was again inspected and noted to have an expanding hematoma of the broad ligament and infundibulopelvic ligament. It was felt that given expanding hematoma a hysterectomy was indicated to stop the expansion. At this point the pt was awake. We discussed the situation with the pt. She said she was planning on a hysterectomy later on for abnormal bleeding anyway. The pt was placed under general anesthesia after verbally consenting to hysterectomy.  The right round ligament was transfixion sutured with 0 Vicryl and divided with cautery (for the remainder of the dictation, all suture will be 0 Vicryl unless otherwise stated).  The anterior leaf broad of the broad ligament and the vesicouterine peritoneum on the patient's left side were incised with a combination of cautery and sharp dissection to a point below the uterine incision and broad ligament hematoma, but above the cervix.  The posterior leaf of the broad ligament was incised with cautery and sharp dissection. A defect was made in the posterior leaf of the broad ligament beneath the uteroovarian ligament and the proximal fallopian tube.  The uteroovarian ligament and the proximal fallopian tube were doubly clamped, incised, and doubly ligated; the second suture was a transfixion suture.The right uterine vessels were skeletonized. The right uterine vessels were doubly clamped, divided, and sutured.  The same process was repeated on the right side.    The left round ligament was transfixion sutured with 0 Vicryl and divided with cautery (for the remainder of the dictation, all suture will be 0 Vicryl unless otherwise stated).  The anterior leaf broad of the broad ligament and the vesicouterine peritoneum on the patient's left side were incised with a combination of cautery and sharp dissection to a point below the uterine incision and broad ligament hematoma, but above the cervix.  The posterior leaf of the broad ligament was incised with cautery and sharp dissection. The right uterine vessels were skeletonized. The left uterine vessels were doubly clamped, divided, and sutured.  The same process was repeated on the right side. A defect was made in the posterior leaf of the broad ligament beneath the uteroovarian ligament and the proximal fallopian tube.  The uteroovarian ligament and the proximal fallopian tube were doubly clamped, incised, and doubly ligated; the second suture was a transfixion suture.    The remainder of the bladder was separated from the underlying cervix with blunt dissection. The paracervical tissue was progressively clamped, incised, and ligated to a level below the uterine incision and broad ligament hematoma, but above the cervix.  Heaney clamps were placed across the uterus and the uterus was amputated using a scalpel. The specimen was handed off the surgical field.  Interrupted imbricating stitches of 0-vicryl were used to close the the uterine amputation site. The angles were closed with figure of eight stitches of 0-vicryl. Areas of bleeding were oversewn with figure of eight stitches of 0-vicryl. The pelvis was irrigated. The right ovary, tube and IP were examined and were noted to be intact without evidence of injury of hematoma. The right ureter was identified and was noted to be far away from the cervical stump and any suture material. Hemostasis along the right pelvic side wall was achieved with cautery and Arista. The left IP and ovary were examined. The IP hematoma had decreased slightly in size, however given concern for possible retroperitoneal extension, the decision was made to proceed with left oophorectomy. A defect was made in the posterior leaf of the broad ligament beneath the infundibulopelvic ligament and above the ureter.  The IP ligament was doubly clamped, incised, and doubly ligated; the second suture was a transfixion suture.  The ureter was identified before clamping and cutting the IP ligament. The ureter was also identified at the level of the cervical stump and was noted to be far away from the angles. Inspection of the entire field revealed hemostasis. There was a hematoma in the left retroperitoneum that was stable and becoming smaller. All pedicles were hemostatic as was the cervical stump at the completion. Throughout case there was communication with anesthesia regarding blood loss and patient recieved prbcs and FFP was ordered.    The fascia was closed with one suture of 0-vicryl starting at the angle and running continuously.  The subcutaneous tissue was irrigated and hemostasis was assured.  The subcutaneous tissue was reapproximated with a running stitch of 3-0 Vicryl.  The skin was closed with 4-0 polysorb. Benzoin, Steri-Strips, and a sterile dressing were applied to the incision.   . An x-ray was performed that showed no retained instruments of laps. The patient was, awakened from anesthesia, and transferred to the SICU in a stable condition.  All counts were correct at the end of the procedure.  [**NAME**], MD

SPECIMENS TO PATHOLOGY:  INDICATIONS: [**NAME**] is a 34 y.o. female para 3013 with three prior cesarean deliveries, Hepatitis C, and undesired fertility. She presented to Labor and Delivery for a scheduled repeat cesarean and bilateral tubal interruption.  DESCRIPTION OF THE PROCEDURE: The patient was identified and brought to the operating room and placed on the operating table.  A time-out was taken and the patient's identity and planned surgical procedure were confirmed.  After the establishment of adequate regional anesthesia, the patient was placed in the dorsal supine position in left lateral tilt and her abdomen was prepped and draped in the usual sterile manner.  A second time-out was taken and the patient's identity and planned surgical procedure were confirmed; it was confirmed that her antibiotics were being administered and that her pneumatic compression stockings were in place and functioning.   The abdomen was entered in the routine manner through a Pfannensteil incision. The incision was taken down to the level of the fascia which was incised in the midline. The incision was extended laterally in either direction over the rectus muscles. The fascia was dissected off the rectus muscle superiorly and then inferiorly. The rectus muscle was divided bluntly. The peritoneum was entered in a clear space sharply. Omental adhesions were lysed with electrocautery. A transverse incision was made in the lower uterine segment with a scalpel and the incision was extended bilaterally with the surgeon's fingers.  The amniotic fluid was clear.  The above described infant was delivered from the Cephalic presentation.  The cord was doubly clamped and cut and the baby was handed to the awaiting pediatrician. A sample of cord blood was obtained for infant identification purposes.  The placenta was delivered with gentle traction on the cord, and the uterine cavity was cleared with a clean lap.  The uterus was exteriorized, and the uterine incision was closed in two layers, the first a running suture of 0 Vicryl and the second a running, imbricating suture of 0 Vicryl.   The left fallopian tube was identified to its fimbriated end. A Babcock forcep was placed in the midisthmic portion of the left fallopain tube over a relatively avascular portion of the mesosalpinx. A defect was created bluntly in this area of the mesosalpinx with a hemostat. A portion of the tube was ligated on two sutures of plain gut and the intervening portion of tube was excised with Metzenbaum scissors. The portion of tube was handed off the field and prepared to be sent to Pathology. Hemostasis was ensured at the cut ends of the tube. The same procedure was repeated on the right side.  The uterus was replaced in the abdominal cavity.  Adequate hemostasis was confirmed along the uterine incision, posterior to the bladder, and in the subfascial area.  The closed uterine incision was irrigated. The fascia was closed with two sutures of 0 Vicryl beginning from either end of the incision and meeting in the midportion.  The subcutaneous tissue was irrigated. The skin was closed with staples.  A sterile dressing was applied to the incision.  The vagina was cleared of clots.  All counts were correct and the patient left for the recovery room in good condition.  [**NAME**], MD

Date of Surgery: [**DATE**]  Preoperative Diagnosis: 1) 37 week pregnancy 2) Prior cesarean x 3  4) History of uterine window  5) Undesired fertility  Postoperative Diagnosis: Same  Operation Performed: Low Transverse Cesarean Section, Bilateral Parkland tubal interruption  Surgeon: [**NAME**]  Assistant: [**NAME**]  Anesthesiologist: [**NAME**]  Anesthesiology Assistant: Fair  Anesthesia: Spinal  Pathology: Bilateral segments of tubes  EBL: 1000ml  Findings: Normal uterus, tubes and ovaries bilaterally. Indication: [**NAME**] is a 25 y.o. female para 3003 who was scheduled for repeat cesarean at 37 weeks due to a prior history of uterine window. The patient desired permanent sterilization.  Procedure: After satisfactory anesthesia, the patient was prepped and draped in a routine fashion for abdominal surgery.  Time-out confirmed patient and procedure.  The abdomen was entered with a Pfannenstiel approach. The medial aspect of the each rectus muscle was transected with cautery to access the uterus.  A bladder flap was created and then a transverse incision was made in the lower uterine segment with a scalpel and extended laterally with the surgeon's fingers. The lower uterine segment was very thin but did not have an obvious window.  Amniotic fluid was clear.  The above described infant was delivered from the Cephalic presentation.  The cord was clamped and cut and the baby handed to the pediatrician.  Blood for gases and DNA was obtained.  The placenta was delivered with cord traction.  The uterus was wiped out with a lap.  The uterus was closed in a single layer closure using 0-Monocryl. The right fallopian tube was identified by the fimbria, grasped and elevated with a babcock. The mesosalpinx beneath the isthmic portion of the tube was cauterized with bovey. The tube was double ligated with 1-Plain gut suture and the intervening segment excised. The left fallopian tube was identified by the fimbria, grasped and elevated with a babcock. The mesosalpinx beneath the isthmic portion of the tube was cauterized with bovey. The tube was double ligated with 1-Plain gut suture and the intervening segment excised.   The uterus was reexamined and found to be hemostatic. The fascia was closed with 2 suture/s of 0-Vicryl starting at the angle and running in a continuous fashion. The subcutaneous tissue was irrigated and reapproximated with 0-Chromic. The skin was closed with 4-0 Monocryl.  Steri strips and a bandage were applied.  The vagina was cleared of clots.  All counts were correct and the patient left for the recovery room in good condition.   [**NAME**]  Dictated for [**NAME**] MD I was present for the entire case.  I reviewed the resident's note and made appropriate corrections and additions to it. SPECIMENS TO PATHOLOGY: Placenta   INDICATIONS: [**NAME**] is a 21 y.o. female para 0 at 28w0d who was admitted as a transfer for severe pre-eclampsia.  She was given magnesium sulfate, IV antihypertensives including labetala and hydralazine were administered for severe range BP, she also received her first dose of betamethasone. Fetal status deteriorated with a low baseline in the 100's and absent variability. The decision to proceed with Stat Cesarean Delivery was made following a prolonged deceleration to the 80's.  DESCRIPTION OF THE PROCEDURE: The patient was identified and brought to the operating room and placed on the operating table. A time-out was taken and the patient's identity and planned surgical procedure were confirmed. After the establishment of adequate regional anesthesia, the patient was placed in the dorsal supine position in left lateral tilt and her abdomen was prepped and draped in the usual sterile manner. A second time-out was taken and the patient's identity and planned surgical procedure were confirmed; it was confirmed that her antibiotics were being administered and that her pneumatic compression stockings were in place and functioning.  The abdomen was entered in the routine manner through a STAT Pfannenstiel incision. A bladder flap was not created. A transverse incision was made in the lower uterine segment with a scalpel and the incision was extended bilaterally with the surgeons fingers. The amniotic fluid was clear. The above described infant was delivered from the Cephalic presentation. The cord was doubly clamped and cut and the baby was handed to the awaiting pediatrician. A sample of cord and cord blood was obtained for analysis. The placenta was delivered with gentle traction on the cord, and the uterine cavity was cleared with a clean lap. The uterus was exteriorized, and the uterine incision was closed in 2 layers, the first a running suture of 0 Monocryl and the second a running, imbricating suture of 0 Monocryl.  The uterus was replaced in the abdominal cavity. Adequate hemostasis was confirmed along the uterine incision, posterior to the bladder, and in the subfascial area. The fascia was closed with one suture of 0 Vicryl beginning from one end of the incision and running across to the other side. The subcutaneous tissue was closed with a running suture of 3-0 Vicryl. The skin was closed with a running subcuticular closure of 4-0 Polysorb. Benzoin, Steri-Strips, and a sterile dressing were applied to the incision. The vagina was cleared of clots. All counts were correct and the patient left for the recovery room in good condition. Obstetrics Operative Report   Date of Surgery: [**DATE**]  PREOPERATIVE DIAGNOSIS:  1) Intrauterine pregnancy at 37 weeks 2) Premature Rupture of Membranes 3) Non-Reassuring Fetal Heart Tracing  POSTOPERATIVE DIAGNOSIS:  1) Intrauterine pregnancy at 37 weeks 2) Premature Rupture of Membranes 3) Non-Reassuring Fetal Heart Tracing  PROCEDURE:  1) Low transverse cesarean section  SURGEON: Dr. [**NAME**] ASSISTANT: Dr. [**NAME**]  ANESTHESIOLOGIST: Dr. [**NAME**] ANESTHESIA ASSISTANT: Dr. [**NAME**]  ANESTHESIA: Spinal  EBL: 600mL  FINDINGS: Normal uterus, tubes and ovaries bilaterally.  Liveborn infant male weighing 2824 grams with Apgars of 9 and 9.  SPECIMENS TO PATHOLOGY:  INDICATIONS: [**NAME**] is a 20 y.o. female para 0 who was admitted to labor and dleivery at 37 weeks for premature rupture of membranes. She was augmented with pitocin. However, she developed persistent variable decelerations unresponsive to conservative measures and was remote from delivery at 5 cm. For this reason the patient was taken to the OR for cesarean delivery.  DESCRIPTION OF THE PROCEDURE: The patient was identified and brought to the operating room and placed on the operating table.  A time-out was taken and the patient's identity and planned surgical procedure were confirmed.  After the establishment of adequate regional anesthesia, the patient was placed in the dorsal supine position in left lateral tilt and her abdomen was prepped and draped in the usual sterile manner.  A second time-out was taken and the patient's identity and planned surgical procedure were confirmed; it was confirmed that her antibiotics were being administered and that her pneumatic compression stockings were in place and functioning.   The abdomen was entered in the routine manner through a pfannensteil incision. The incision was taken down to the level of the fascia with sharp dissection; the fascia was scored in the midline. The incision was extended laterally in either direction over the rectus muscles. The fascia was dissected off the rectus muscle superiorly and then inferiorly. The rectus muscle was divided bluntly. The peritoneum was entered in a clear space sharply.  A bladder flap was created.  A transverse incision was made in the lower uterine segment with a scalpel and the incision was extended bilaterally with blunt dissection  The amniotic fluid was clear.  The above described infant was delivered from the Cephalic presentation. The infant gave a spontaneous cry and extremity movement.  The cord was doubly clamped and cut and the baby was handed to the awaiting pediatrician. A sample of cord and cord blood was obtained for analysis.  The placenta was delivered with gentle traction on the cord, and the uterine cavity was cleared with a clean lap.  The uterus was exteriorized, and the uterine incision was closed in 2 layers, the first a running locking suture of 0-vicryl and the second a running, imbricating suture of 0-vicryl.  The uterus was replaced in the abdominal cavity.  Adequate hemostasis was confirmed along the uterine incision, posterior to the bladder, and in the subfascial area.  The fascia was reapproximated with 0 Vicryl starting at the angle and running in a continuous fashion.  The subcutaneous tissue was irrigated.  The skin was closed with a running subcuticular closure of 3-0 monocryl.  Steri-Strips and a sterile dressing were applied to the incision.  The vagina was cleared of clots.  All counts were correct and the patient left for the recovery room in good condition.  [**NAME**], MD   Dictated for Dr. [**NAME**]  Attending Addendum  I was present and scrubbed throughout the entire procedure and agree with the above operative note. Obstetrics Operative Report   Date of Surgery: [**DATE**]  PREOPERATIVE DIAGNOSIS:  1) Intrauterine pregnancy at 38 weeks 4 days 2) Idiopathic polyhydramnios  3) Arrest of dilation 4) Arrest of descent  5) Repetitive Variable Decelerations    POSTOPERATIVE DIAGNOSIS:  1) Intrauterine pregnancy at 38 weeks 4 days 2) Idiopathic polyhydramnios  3) Arrest of dilation 4) Arrest of descent  5) Repetitive Variable Decelerations  6) Delivered   PROCEDURE:  1) Low transverse cesarean section  SURGEON: Dr. [**NAME**]  ASSISTANT: Dr. [**NAME**] and Dr. [**NAME**]   ANESTHESIOLOGIST: Dr. [**NAME**]  ANESTHESIA ASSISTANT: Dr. [**NAME**]   ANESTHESIA: Epidural   EBL: 800mL  FINDINGS: Normal uterus. Ovaries and tubes were not visualized. Liveborn infant male weighing 3764 grams with Apgars of 9 and 9.  SPECIMENS TO PATHOLOGY: Placenta   INDICATIONS: [**NAME**] is a 31 y.o. female para 1001 at 38 weeks. She was undergoing induction secondary to a history of polyhydramnios that had required amnioreduction. She progressed to 9 cm and did not dilate further. The fetal heart tracing showed repetitive deep variable decelerations to the 60s. She did not have adequate contractions but the pitocin could not be titrated secondary to the fetal heart tracing.   DESCRIPTION OF THE PROCEDURE: The patient was identified and brought to the operating room and placed on the operating table.  A time-out was taken and the patient's identity and planned surgical procedure were confirmed.  After the establishment of adequate regional anesthesia, the patient was placed in the dorsal supine position in left lateral tilt and her abdomen was prepped and draped in the usual sterile manner.  A second time-out was taken and the patient's identity and planned surgical procedure were confirmed; it was confirmed that her antibiotics were being administered and that her pneumatic compression stockings were in place and functioning.   The abdomen was entered in the routine manner through a Pfannenstiel incision. The incision was taken down to the level of the fascia which was incised in the midline. The incision was extended laterally in either direction over the rectus muscles. The fascia was dissected off the rectus muscle superiorly and then inferiorly. The rectus muscle was divided bluntly. The peritoneum was entered in a clear space sharply.  A bladder flap was created.  A transverse incision was made in the lower uterine segment with a scalpel and the incision was extended bilaterally with the surgeon's fingers.  The amniotic fluid was clear.  The above described infant was delivered from the Cephalic presentation.  The cord was doubly clamped and cut and the baby was handed to the awaiting pediatrician. A sample of cord and cord blood was obtained for analysis. Cord blood collection was performed.  The placenta was delivered with gentle traction on the cord, and the uterine cavity was cleared with a clean lap.  The uterus was not exteriorized.  The uterine incision was closed in two layers, the first a locking suture of 0-vicryl and the second a running, imbricating suture of 0-vicryl. Adequate hemostasis was confirmed along the uterine incision, posterior to the bladder, and in the subfascial area.  The fascia was closed with two sutures of 0 Vicryl beginning from either end of the incision and meeting in the midportion.  The subcutaneous tissue was irrigated and re-approximated with a running suture of 0-chromic.  The skin was closed with a running subcuticular closure of 4-0 Monocryl.  Dermabond was applied to the incision.  The vagina was cleared of clots.  All counts were correct and the patient left for the recovery room in good condition.  [**NAME**], MD   Dictated for Dr. [**NAME**]   I was present and scrubbed for the entire procedure. Gestational Diabetes  Postoperative Diagnosis: Same  Operation Performed: Repeat Low Transverse cesarean section, Bilateral Parkland Tubal Interruption  Surgeon: Dr. [**NAME**]  Assisstant: Dr. [**NAME**]  Anesthesia: Spinal  Pathology: bilateral segments of tube, placenta  EBL: 800ml  Findings: Normal uterus, tubes and ovaries bilaterally. Baby A: Liveborn infant female weighing 2044 grams with Apgars of 9 and 9. Baby B: Liveborn infant female weighing 2376 grams with Apgars of 9 and 9.  Indication: [**NAME**] is a 30 y.o. female para 2022 who presented to labor and delivery for evaluation of newly elevated blood pressure and was found to have severely elevated blood pressures with neurologic symptoms (headachee, hyper-reflexia & clonus) consistent with severe pre-eclampsia. Indication for delivery was severe pre-eclampsia after 34 weeks, via cesarean for di/di twins, malpresentation (breech) of twin A and prior cesarean delivery, the pt was taken to the OR for repeat cesarean delivery with BTI.  Procedure: After satisfactory anesthesia, the patient was prepped and draped in a routine fashion for abdominal surgery.  Time-out confirmed patient and procedure.  The abdomen was entered with a pfannensteil approach.  A bladder flap was created and then a transverse incision was made in the lower uterine segment with a scalpel and extended laterally with the surgeon's fingers.  Amniotic fluid was clear.  The above described infant A was delivered from the Breech presentation.  The cord was clamped after 30 seconds and cut and the baby handed to the pediatrician.  Blood for gases and DNA was obtained.  The above described infant B was delivered from the Cephalic presentation.  The cord was clamped after 30 seconds and cut and the baby handed to the pediatrician.  Blood for gases and DNA was obtained. The placenta was delivered with cord traction.  The uterus was wiped out with a lap.  The uterus was closed in a single layer closure using 0-vicrly.   The right fallopian tube was identified by the fimbria, double ligated with 0-chromic suture and the intervening segment excised.  The left fallopian tube was identified by the fimbria, double ligated with 0-chromic suture and the intervening segment excised.    The fascia was closed with 1 suture of 0-Vicryl starting at the angle and running in a continuous fashion. The subcutaneous tissue was irrigated.  The skin was closed with 4-0 polysorb.  Steri strips and a bandage were applied.  The vagina was cleared of clots.  All counts were correct and the patient left for the recovery room in good condition. Date of Surgery: [**DATE**]  PREOPERATIVE DIAGNOSIS:  1) Intrauterine pregnancy at 39 weeks 4 days 2) Prior LTCS x 1 2) Undesired fertility  POSTOPERATIVE DIAGNOSIS:  1) Intrauterine pregnancy at 39 weeks 4 days 2) Repeat low transverse cesarean section 3) Undesired fertility  PROCEDURE:  1) Low transverse cesarean section 2) Parkland postpartum bilateral tubal interruption  SURGEON: [**NAME**] MD ASSISTANT: [**NAME**] MD  ANESTHESIOLOGIST: [**NAME**] MD ANESTHESIA ASSISTANT: [**NAME**] MD  ANESTHESIA: Spinal  EBL: 300 mL  FLUID REPLACEMENT: 2300 mL  FINDINGS: Normal uterus, tubes and ovaries bilaterally.  Liveborn infant female weighing 3697 grams with Apgars of 7 and 9.  SPECIMENS TO PATHOLOGY:  Segments from each tube  INDICATIONS: [**NAME**] is a 31 y.o. female para 1001 who presented for scheduled repeat cesarean section. She had a prior LTCS x 1 and declined a trial of labor after cesarean section.   DESCRIPTION OF THE PROCEDURE: The patient was identified and brought to the operating room and placed on the operating table.  A time-out was taken and the patient's identity and planned surgical procedure were confirmed.  After the establishment of adequate regional anesthesia, the patient was placed in the dorsal supine position in left lateral tilt and her abdomen was prepped and draped in the usual sterile manner.  A second time-out was taken and the patient's identity and planned surgical procedure were confirmed; it was confirmed that her antibiotics were being administered and that her pneumatic compression stockings were in place and functioning.   The abdomen was entered in the routine manner through a Pfanenstiel incision.  A bladder flap was not created.  A transverse incision was made in the lower uterine segment with a scalpel and the incision was extended bilaterally with traction.  The amniotic fluid was clear.  The above described infant was delivered from the Cephalic presentation.  The cord was doubly clamped and cut and the baby was handed to the awaiting pediatrician. A sample of cord and cord blood was obtained for analysis.  The placenta was delivered with gentle traction on the cord, and the uterine cavity was cleared with a clean lap x 2.  The uterus was exteriorized, and the uterine incision was closed in two layers, the first a running suture of 0 Vicryl and the second a running, imbricating suture of 0 Monocryl.    The right fallopian tube was identified to its fimbriated end and a defect was made in a relatively avascular portion of the mesosalpinx underlying the mid isthmic portion of the tube.  A segment of the mid isthmic portion of the tube was ligated with two sutures of 1 Plain Gut suture and the intervening portion of the tube excised and handed off the field; adequate hemostasis was assured.  The exact same procedure was performed on the opposite side after identifying that tube to its fimbriated end; again, adequate hemostasis was assured.  The uterus was replaced in the abdominal cavity.  Adequate hemostasis was confirmed along the uterine incision and in the subfascial area.  The fascia was re-approximated with one suture of 0 Vicryl beginning from one corner of the incision and running to the opposite corner.  The subcutaneous tissue was not reapproximated due to subcutaneous tissue with depth less than 1 cm.  The skin was closed with a running subcuticular closure of 3-0 Monocryl.  Benzoin, Steri-Strips, and a sterile dressing were applied to the incision.  The vagina was cleared of clots.  All counts were correct and the patient left for the recovery room in good condition.  [**NAME**] M.D.

Date of Surgery: [**DATE**]  Preoperative Diagnosis:  1) 40 weeks  2) Arrest of dilation  3) Chorioamnionitis  Postoperative Diagnosis: Same   Operation Performed: Primary Low Transverse Cesarean Section  Surgeon: [**NAME**]  Assistant: [**NAME**]   Anesthesiologist: [**NAME**]  Anesthesiology Assistant: [**NAME**]  Anesthesia: Spinal   Pathology: Placenta   EBL: 800 ml  Findings: Normal uterus, tubes and ovaries bilaterally.  Liveborn infant female weighing 3456 grams with Apgars of 8 and 9.  Indication: [**NAME**] is a 26 y.o. female para 0 who was admitted with spontaneous rupture of membranes at 3/C/-1. She was started on pitocin and progressed to 5/C/0 but did not progress further despite adequate uterine contractions on pitocin. She developed chorioamnionitis and was started on antibiotics. After 5 hours of no cervical change she was agreeable to delivery via cesarean section.   Procedure: After satisfactory anesthesia, the patient was prepped and draped in a routine fashion for abdominal surgery.  Time-out confirmed patient and procedure.  The abdomen was entered with a Pfannensteil approach.  A bladder flap was created and then a transverse incision was made in the lower uterine segment with a scalpel and extended laterally with the surgeon's fingers.  Amniotic fluid was cloudy white.  The above described infant was delivered from the cephalic presentation.  The cord was clamped and cut and the baby handed to the pediatrician.  Blood for gases and DNA was obtained.  The placenta was delivered with cord traction.  The uterus was wiped out with a lap.  The uterus was closed in a double layer closure using 0-monocryl. The first layer was sewn in a running locked fashion from angle to angle. The second layer was an imbricating layer sewn across the hysterotomy. The fascia was closed with 1 suture of 0-Vicryl starting at the angle and running in a continuous fashion. The subcutaneous tissue was irrigated and reapproximated with a single running stitch of 3-0 vicryl.  The skin was closed with 4-0 monocryl in an intracuticular fashion.  Steristrips (without benzoin) were applied and an OpSite dressing was applied.  The vagina was cleared of clots.  All counts were correct and the patient left for the recovery room in good condition.  [**NAME**]  Dictated for [**NAME**] MD  I was present for the entire case.  I reviewed the resident's note and made appropriate corrections and additions to it.   [**NAME**], M.D. Maternal Fetal Medicine Fellow Adjunct Clinical Associate Department of Obstetrics and Gynecology [**LOCATION_INSTITUTE**] College of Medicine

SPECIMENS TO PATHOLOGY: placenta  INDICATIONS: [**NAME**] is a 22 y.o. female para 0 at 41w2d who progressed to complete and developed chorioamnionitis.  She pushed for 3 hours with no change in descent and the decision was made to proceed with cesarean delivery  DESCRIPTION OF THE PROCEDURE: The patient was identified and brought to the operating room and placed on the operating table.  A time-out was taken and the patient's identity and planned surgical procedure were confirmed.  After the establishment of adequate regional anesthesia, the patient was placed in the dorsal supine position in left lateral tilt and her abdomen was prepped and draped in the usual sterile manner.  A second time-out was taken and the patient's identity and planned surgical procedure were confirmed; it was confirmed that her antibiotics were being administered and that her pneumatic compression stockings were in place and functioning.   The abdomen was entered in the routine manner through a Pfanenstiel incision.  A bladder flap was created.  A transverse incision was made in the lower uterine segment with a scalpel and the incision was extended bilaterally with bandage scissors.  The amniotic fluid was thick meconium stained.  The above described infant was delivered from the Cephalic presentation.  The cord was doubly clamped and cut and the baby was handed to the awaiting pediatrician. A sample of cord and cord blood was obtained for analysis.  The placenta was delivered with gentle traction on the cord, and the uterine cavity was cleared with a clean lap.  The uterus was exteriorized, and it was noted that there was a 3 cm extension on the left lateral edge of the hysterotomy.  It was closed separately with a running suture of 0-Monocryl.  Then, the uterine incision was closed in two layers, the first a running suture of 0 Monocryl and the second a running, imbricating suture of 0 Monocryl.    Atony was noted and additional 40 units of pitocin was administered.  Methergine was given x 1 and hemabate was given x 2, 15 minutes apart, one IM and one intrauterine.  Tone improved after the uterus was replaced in the abdominal cavity.    Adequate hemostasis was confirmed along the uterine incision and in the subfascial area.  Additional figure of eight sutures were placed on the rectus muscle for hemostasis.  The fascia was closed with one suture of 0 Vicryl beginning from one end of the incision and running across.  The subcutaneous tissue was closed with a running suture of 3-0 Vicryl.  The skin was closed with a running subcuticular closure of 4-0 Polysorb.  Benzoin, Steri-Strips, and a sterile dressing were applied to the incision.  The vagina was cleared of clots.  1000 mcg of misoprostol was placed rectally at the end of the case.  All counts were correct and the patient left for the recovery room in good condition. Date of Surgery: [**DATE**]  Preoperative Diagnosis:  1) IUP at 40 weeks  2) Polyhydramnios 3) Arrest of dilation  4) Failed induction of labor   Postoperative Diagnosis: Same   Operation Performed: Primary Low Transverse Cesarean Section  Surgeon: [**NAME**]  Assistant: [**NAME**]   Anesthesiologist: [**NAME**]  Anesthesiology Assistant: [**NAME**]   Anesthesia: Spinal   Pathology: Placenta   EBL: 1000 ml  Findings: Normal uterus, tubes and ovaries bilaterally.  Liveborn infant male weighing 4183 grams with Apgars of 9 and 9.  Indication: [**NAME**] is a 28 y.o. female para 0 who presented at 40 weeks for scheduled induction of labor for idiopathic polyhydramnios. She progressed to 5 cm but had no descent with fetal station at -3 and ballotable. She made no progress on pitocin for greater than 12 hours and was offered primary cesarean for failure to progress.   Procedure: After satisfactory anesthesia, the patient was prepped and draped in a routine fashion for abdominal surgery.  Time-out confirmed patient and procedure.  The abdomen was entered with a Pfannensteil approach. The fascia was scored with a scalpel and cut laterally with curved mayo scissors. The fascia was dissected off the underlying muscle. The rectus muscles were separated and the peritoneum incised with Metzenbaum scissors. The peritoneum was stretched and a bladder blade placed in the lower aspect of the abdominal cavity to expose the lower uterine segment. The uterus was palpated and was found to be extremely dextrorotated.  A bladder flap was created and then a transverse incision was made in the lower uterine segment with a scalpel and extended laterally with the surgeon's fingers.  Amniotic fluid was copious and clear.  The above described infant was delivered from the vertex presentation with the aid of a Kiwi vacuum.  The cord was clamped and cut and the baby handed to the pediatrician.  Blood for gases and DNA was obtained.  The placenta was delivered with cord traction and sent to pathology.  The uterus was wiped out with a lap.  Uterine atony was diagnosed and 40 units of pitocin was started on a pressure bag with fundal massage. A B-Lynch stitch was placed in the usual fashion using #1 chromic gut suture and tied down. The uterus was closed in a double layer closure. The first stitch was a running, unlocked stitch of 0-vicryl. The second an imbricating layer of 0-vicryl.  The fascia was closed with 2 sutures of 0-Vicryl starting at the angle and running in a continuous fashion to meet at midline. The subcutaneous tissue was irrigated and reapproximated with a running stitch of 3-0 vicryl.  The skin was closed with a running intracuticular stitch of 3-0 monocryl.  Steristrips and a sterile dressing were applied.  The vagina was cleared of clots.  All counts were correct and the patient left for the recovery room in good condition. Indication: [**NAME**] is a 28 y.o. female para 0111 who presented at 35 weeks with complaints of back pain and was found to be in preterm labor. Her cervix was 4 cm 90% and given prior myomectomy she was taken for cesarean delivery.   Procedure: After satisfactory anesthesia, the patient was prepped and draped in a routine fashion for abdominal surgery.  Time-out confirmed patient and procedure.  The abdomen was entered with a Pfannensteil approach using the prior transverse abdominal incision.  A bladder flap was not created and then a transverse incision was made in the lower uterine segment with a scalpel and extended laterally with the surgeon's fingers.  Amniotic fluid was clear.  The above described infant was delivered from the cephalic presentation.  The cord was clamped and cut and the baby handed to the pediatrician.  Blood for gases and DNA was obtained.  The placenta was delivered with cord traction.  The uterus was wiped out with a lap.  The uterus was closed in a double layer closure using 0-vicryl.  The first layer was ran in an unlocking, continuous fashion and the second was an imbricating layer.  Thin filmy adhesions between the uterine fundus and omentum were taken down with Bovie cautery.  The fascia was closed with a running suture of 0-Vicryl.  The subcutaneous tissue was irrigated and reapproximated with a running stitch of 3-0 Vicryl.  The skin was closed with a running intracuticular stitch of 3-0 Monocryl.  Steristrips were applied.  The vagina was cleared of clots.  All counts were correct and the patient left for the recovery room in good condition.  [**NAME**]  Dictated for [**NAME**] MD   I was present for the entire case. Obstetrics Operative Report   Date of Surgery: [**DATE**]  PREOPERATIVE DIAGNOSIS:  1) Intrauterine pregnancy at 34 weeks 5 days 2) PPROM 3) Nonreassuring FHT 4) Suspected placental abruption  POSTOPERATIVE DIAGNOSIS:  Sam + confirmed placental abruption  PROCEDURE:  1) Stat primary low transverse cesarean section  SURGEON: [**NAME**] ASSISTANT: [**NAME**]  ANESTHESIOLOGIST: [**NAME**] ANESTHESIA ASSISTANT: [**NAME**]  ANESTHESIA: GETA  EBL: 1000 mL  FLUID REPLACEMENT: 3000 mL  FINDINGS: 2 small (1-3cm) pedunculated fibroids on anterior uterus. Normal tubes and ovaries bilaterally with exception of small bilateral paratubal cysts.  Liveborn infant female weighing 2151grams with Apgars of 8 and 9.  SPECIMENS TO PATHOLOGY: placenta  INDICATIONS: [**NAME**] is a 24 y.o. female para 1001 who presented with PPROM at 34w5d. Was started on pitocin to augment labor and progressed to 6 cm but began to have repetitive decelerations and noted to have approx 150-200cc blood out with clots suspicious for abruption. Decision was made to proceed to OR for cesarean delivery. Developed more persistent bradycardia en route to OR and proceeded to stat cesarean.   DESCRIPTION OF THE PROCEDURE: The patient was identified and brought to the operating room and placed on the operating table.  A time-out was taken and the patient's identity and planned surgical procedure were confirmed.  After the establishment of adequate regional anesthesia, the patient was placed in the dorsal supine position in left lateral tilt and her abdomen was prepped and draped in the usual sterile manner.  A second time-out was taken and the patient's identity and planned surgical procedure were confirmed; it was confirmed that her antibiotics were being administered and that her pneumatic compression stockings were in place and functioning.   The abdomen was entered in the routine manner through a Pfannenstiel incision. The incision was taken down to the level of the fascia which was incised in the midline. The incision was extended laterally in either direction over the rectus muscles. The fascia was dissected off the rectus muscle superiorly and then inferiorly. The rectus muscle was divided bluntly. The peritoneum was entered in a clear space bluntly.  A bladder flap was not created.  A transverse incision was made in the lower uterine segment with a scalpel and the incision was extended bilaterally with the surgeon's fingers.  The amniotic fluid was clear.  The above described infant was delivered from the Cephalic presentation.  The cord was doubly clamped and cut and the baby was handed to the awaiting pediatrician. A sample of cord and cord blood was obtained for analysis.  The placenta was delivered with gentle traction on the cord, and the uterine cavity was cleared with a clean lap.  The uterus was exteriorized, and the uterine incision was closed in 2 layers, the first a running, locking suture of 0-vicryl and the second a running, imbricating suture of 0-vicryl.  The uterus was replaced in the abdominal cavity.  Adequate hemostasis was confirmed along the uterine incision, posterior to the bladder, and in the subfascial area.  The fascia was closed with one suture of 0 Vicryl beginning from either one of the incision and running continuously.  The subcutaneous tissue was irrigated and did not require re-approximation.  The skin was closed with a running subcuticular closure of 3-0 monocryl.  Benzoin, Steri-Strips, and a sterile dressing were applied to the incision.  The vagina was cleared of clots.  All counts were correct and the patient left for the recovery room in good condition.  [**NAME**], MD  Dictated for Dr. [**NAME**]

P0 at 35w0d with a history of T2DM on glyburide and gestational hypertension and DM who had been monitored on L&D for variable decels in her clinic NST a couple days prior.  Tracing had been moderate variability with occasional variable decels until evening of [**DATE**] when variability decreased.  A biophysical profile was performed and was [**DATE**] (2 points off for breathing and 2 points off for movement). Delivery was indicated and while discussing possible route of delivery with the patient, she had a prolonged deceleration and was transported to the OR.  In the OR FHTs were in the 130s with moderate variability.  At that time cesarean delivery was recommended because of suspected fetal intolerance of labor very remote from delivery.  Because of the normal FHR at that time, it was determined that there was time to establish regional anesthesia and reduce maternal aspiration risks, and anesthesia placed a spinal in less than 5 minutes and we proceeded rapidly with cesarean delivery.  DESCRIPTION OF THE PROCEDURE: The patient was identified and brought to the operating room and placed on the operating table.  A time-out was taken and the patient's identity and planned surgical procedure were confirmed.  After the establishment of adequate regional anesthesia, the patient was placed in the dorsal supine position in left lateral tilt and her abdomen was prepped and draped in the usual sterile manner.  A second time-out was taken and the patient's identity and planned surgical procedure were confirmed; it was confirmed that her antibiotics were being administered and that her pneumatic compression stockings were in place and functioning.   The abdomen was entered in the routine manner through a Pfannenstiel incision. The incision was taken down to the level of the fascia which was incised in the midline. The incision was extended laterally in either direction over the rectus muscles. The fascia was dissected off the rectus muscle superiorly and then inferiorly. The rectus muscle was divided bluntly. The peritoneum was entered in a clear space sharply.  A bladder flap was not created.  A transverse incision was made in the lower uterine segment with a scalpel and the incision was extended bilaterally with the surgeon's fingers and bandage scissors.  The amniotic fluid was clear.  The above described infant was delivered from the Cephalic presentation.  Delayed cord clamping was considered, however there was little blood in the umbilical cord and the baby was limp so the cord was doubly clamped and cut and the baby was handed to the awaiting NICU 111 team. A sample of cord and cord blood was obtained for analysis.  The placenta was delivered with gentle traction on the cord, and the uterine cavity was cleared with a clean lap.  The uterus was exteriorized, and the uterine incision was closed in 2 layers, the first a running suture of 0-Vicryl and the second a running, imbricating suture of 0-Vicryl.   The uterus was replaced in the abdominal cavity.  Adequate hemostasis was confirmed along the uterine incision, posterior to the bladder, and in the subfascial area.  The fascia was closed with one suture of 0 Vicryl beginning at one end of the incision and running to the other.  The subcutaneous tissue was irrigated and re-approximated with a running suture of 3-0 Vicryl.  The skin was closed with a running subcuticular closure of 3-0 Monocryl. Dermabond was applied to the incision. The vagina was cleared of clots.  All counts were correct and the patient left for the recovery room in good condition. MOB stated that when she arrived on L&D, before she delivered her baby, MOB informed her nurse that she had her own prescription of methadone and would not need the medical staff to give her any doses. MOB stated no one made a big deal out of this and she took her medication as prescribed. When MOB arrived on the Mother-Baby Unit, MOB stated that she expected that she would continue taking her own medication. SW explained to MOB that her MBU nurse was following hospital protocol. SW explained that patients are not allowed to take their own medications (even ibuprofen or Tylenol) because of the danger of getting double doses. MOB stated she now understands. SW thanked MOB for her honesty about having her own medication with her.   To be clear, MOB did not take a double dose of methadone. She was honest about taking her own medication and refused the medication so she would not be double dosed.  During this assessment, SW observed MOB and her daughters caring for and bonding with baby. SW also observed MOB appropriately disciplining her daughters (who are very well behaved and clean).   SW educated MOB about SIDS, Back to Sleep, Shaken Baby Syndrome, protecting baby from 2nd and 3rd-hand smoke, and Post-Partum Depression.  SW needs to contact Meridian to verify MOB's participation and compliance with the Methadone Clinic. Please contact SW before baby's discharge.

Obstetrics Operative Report   Date of Surgery: [**DATE**]  PREOPERATIVE DIAGNOSIS:  1) Suspected 4th Degree Perineal Laceration  2) Postpartum   POSTOPERATIVE DIAGNOSIS:  1) 4th Degree Perineal Laceration 2) Right Vaginal Sulcal Laceration 2) Postpartum    PROCEDURE:  1) Exam under Anesthesia 2) Repair of 4th Degree Perineal Laceration  3) Repair of Right Vaginal Sulcal Laceration   SURGEON: [**NAME**] MD  ASSISTANT: [**NAME**] MD   ANESTHESIOLOGIST: White MD ANESTHESIA ASSISTANT: [**NAME**] MD  ANESTHESIA: Epidural   EBL: 30 mL  FLUID REPLACEMENT: 1000 mL  FINDINGS: 4th degree perineal laceration and laceration of right vaginal sulcus  SPECIMENS TO PATHOLOGY: None  COMPLICATIONS: None   INDICATIONS: [**NAME**] is a 28 y.o. P1001 who had a vaginal delivery complicated by a mild shoulder dystocia. She was found to have at least a third degree laceration immediately postpartum, but was taken to the operating room for further diagnosis and repair with the aid of optimal anesthesia, lighting, and positioning   DESCRIPTION OF THE PROCEDURE: The patient was identified and brought to the operating room and placed on the operating table.  A time-out was taken and the patient's identity and planned surgical procedure were confirmed.  After the establishment of adequate regional anesthesia, the patient was placed in low lithotomy position and her abdomen and legs were prepped and draped in the usual sterile manner.  An exam under anesthesia was performed, confirming the fourth degree perineal laceration. The rectal mucosa was re-approximated with a running suture of 4-0 Vicryl. The rectal submucosal tissue was re-approximated with a running suture of 3-0 Vicryl. The muscle of the external anal sphincter and the overlying supporting capsule were re-approximated with interrupted sutures of 2-0 Vicryl placed through the capsule.  Attention was then turned to the right sulcal laceration, which was repaired with a running, locked suture of 3-0 Vicryl. Finally, the 2nd degree perineal laceration was repaired in the usual fashion with a running suture of 3-0 Vicryl.  A rectal examination was performed, and no suture or defects were palpable.  A Foley catheter was placed in her bladder.  All counts were correct at the end of procedure. The patient was taken down from low lithotomy position and transferred to the recovery room in good condition.  [**NAME**], MD  Dictated for Dr. [**NAME**]   I was present for the entire case. Date of Surgery: [**DATE**]  Preoperative Diagnosis: Intrauterine pregnancy at 38 weeks, prior cesarean delivery with vertical extension  Postoperative Diagnosis: Same, plus delivered  Operation Performed: Repeat Low Transverse Cesarean Section  Surgeon: [**NAME**]  Assisstant: [**NAME**]  Anesthesiologist: [**NAME**]  Anesthesiology Assisstant: [**NAME**]  Anesthesia: Spinal  Pathology: none  EBL: 800ml  Findings: Normal uterus, tubes and ovaries bilaterally.  Liveborn infant female weighing 2798 grams with Apgars of 6 and 9.  Indication: [**NAME**] is a 37 y.o. female para 2002 at 38w0d who presents for scheduled repeat cesarean delivery for history of cesarean delivery with vertical extension.  Procedure: After satisfactory anesthesia, the patient was prepped and draped in a routine fashion for abdominal surgery.  Time-out confirmed patient and procedure.  The abdomen was entered with a low-transverse approach.  A bladder flap was not created and then a transverse incision was made in the lower uterine segment with a scalpel and extended laterally.  Amniotic fluid was clear.  The above described infant was delivered from the Cephalic presentation.  The cord was clamped and cut and the baby handed to the pediatrician.  Blood for gases and DNA was obtained.  The placenta was delivered with cord traction.  The uterus was wiped out with a lap.  The uterus was closed in a double layer closure using 0-vicryl.  The fascia was closed with 1 suture of 0-Vicryl starting at the angle and running in a continuous fashion. The subcutaneous tissue was irrigated with normal saline.  The skin was closed with Polysorb.  Steri-strips were applied.  The vagina was cleared of clots.  All counts were correct and the patient left for the recovery room in good condition.   [**NAME**]

Liveborn infant male weighing 1697 grams with Apgars of 8 and 9. Liveborn infant male weighing 1535 grams with Apgars of 8 and 9.   SPECIMENS TO PATHOLOGY: Placenta   INDICATIONS: [**NAME**] is a 27 y.o. female para 2032 with a history of di/di twin pregnancy who was admitted in preterm labor. She received a steroid course and was transferred to the floor. Tonight, she began having contractions for about 20 minutes and was brought to Labor and Delivery and found to be completely dilated. She desired delivery via cesarean. Given rapid progression decision was made with anesthesia team to proceed with general anesthesia.  DESCRIPTION OF THE PROCEDURE: The patient was identified and brought to the operating room and placed on the operating table.  A time-out was taken and the patient's identity and planned surgical procedure were confirmed.  The patient was placed in the dorsal supine position and her abdomen was prepped and draped in the usual sterile manner.  A second time-out was taken and the patient's identity and planned surgical procedure were confirmed; it was confirmed that her antibiotics were being administered and that her pneumatic compression stockings were in place and functioning. General anesthesia was then administered.  The abdomen was entered in the routine manner through a Pfannensteil incision. The incision was taken down to the level of the fascia which was incised in the midline. The incision was extended laterally in either direction over the rectus muscles.  The rectus muscle was divided bluntly. The peritoneum was entered in a clear space bluntly.  A bladder flap was not created.  A transverse incision was made in the lower uterine segment with a scalpel and the incision was extended bilaterally with the surgeon's fingers. Immediately 500cc blood clot was found in the uterus consistant with an acute placental abruption. The amniotic fluid was bloody . The above described infant was delivered from the Cephalic presentation.  The cord was doubly clamped and cut and the baby was handed to the awaiting pediatrician. The second amniotic sac was ruptured with clear fluid. The second twin was delivered from the breech presentation. The cord was doubly clamped and cut and the baby was handed to the awaiting pediatrician. A sample of cord and cord blood was obtained for analysis from both cords.  The placenta was delivered with gentle traction on the cord, and the uterine cavity was cleared with a clean lap.  The uterus was exteriorized, and the uterine incision was closed in two layers, the first a locking suture of 0-Vicryl and the second a running, imbricating suture of 0-vicryl. Hemostasis was achieved with a figure of eight suture of 3-0 vicryl.  The uterus was replaced in the abdominal cavity.  Adequate hemostasis was confirmed along the uterine incision, posterior to the bladder, and in the subfascial area. The muscle was found to be bleeding and hemostasis was achieved with electrocautery. Arista was applied to the area for further hemostasis.  The fascia was closed with a running suture of 0 Vicryl.  The subcutaneous tissue was irrigated and hemostasis noted. The skin was closed with staples.  A sterile dressing was applied to the incision.  The vagina was cleared of clots.  All counts were correct and the patient left for the recovery room in good condition. Procedure: After satisfactory anesthesia, the patient was prepped and draped in a routine fashion for abdominal surgery.  Time out confirmed the patient and procedure.  The abdomen was entered with a transverse incision below the umbilicus. Discharge Instructions for patients Who Have Had a Cesarean Delivery  You may immediately resume your usual diet.  You may shower only for the next two weeks, no tub baths, hot tubs, or swimming pools.   You may climb stairs as much as necessary to maintain your usual household routine.  You may drive your care when you are no longer taking narcotic pain-relievers and you feel you can step on the brake forcefully.  You may resume intercourse (sex) as soon as your abdominal discomfort resolves and you feel emotionally interested in having intimate relations.  For the first two weeks after surgery, you should not engage in strenuous exercise or extremely heaving lifting (e.g. Heavy grocery bags, heavy household furniture, older children weighing more than 35 pounds, heavy barbells or dumbbells).  However, you may engage in normal household activities and lift light weights (such as your new baby).  You should take a multivitamin that contains folic acid (400micrograms) and elemental iron (60mg) each day, particularly while you are breast feeding.   If your doctor prescribed oral contraceptives for birth control, please start the medication as directed.   If you are taking a narcotic or a non-steroidal anti-inflammatory agent, such as Ibuprofen (Motrin) for pain relief, please be certain to take the medication with food to avoid irritation of the gastrointestinal tract.   If you are using Tylenol (acetaminophen) for pain relief, please limit your total daily dose to 4 grams or less.  This dose equates to a maximum of 2 regular strength Tylenol tablets every 4 hours for 2 extra-strength Tylenol tablets or capsules every 6 hours.  Please notify your doctor if any of the following problems develop: -Fever -unusually heavy vaginal bleeding (greater than a heavy menstrual period) -pain,tenderness, and redness in the breast -swelling, pain, and tenderness in either lower extremity -pain, redness, warmth, or extreme tenderness in the area where sutures were placed.  Infant needs to be seen by a physician within 24-48 hours of leaving the hospital. Please call your pediatrician and make an appointment for your baby to be seen as instructed by your doctor in the hospital.   Call your doctor or seek medical attention immediately is your baby has: - Temperature equal to or greater than 100.4 F rectally - Increased sleepiness/lethargy - Bloody stools - Breathing problems - Poor feeding - No urine in 24 hours - Increasing yellow color of the skin/eyes - Redness, swelling or foul odor around the umbilical cord - Vomiting - Constipation - Inconsolable crying  Infant Safety: - Always place baby on back to sleep. - No smoking near the baby - Place infant in a rear facing carseat (or carbed) as instructed when traveling. An infant car seat is required by Florida law.   Feeding Infants require only breast milk or formula the first 6 months. Do NOT give babies water or cereal unless your doctor recommends it.  - Breast feed on demand. Increase your own fluid intake. Breast stools are usually yellow and loose. - Aim for 8-12 breast feeding sessions per 24 hours. - If you give your baby formula, feed 1-2oz every 2-3 hours on demand.  Temperature Control Any infant who has difficulty staying warm or has a temperature over 38 C or 100.4F may be ill. Report problems with temperature immediately.  - In cool places, keep baby wrapped with a hat. - Keep baby away from people with colds, flu or other illnesses.   Umbilical Care - Keep umbilical cord dry. You do not need to apply alcohol or anything else to the umbilical cord. It will fall off between 7-14 days of life. - Sponge bathe until the cord falls off.  Return to clinic in 2-5 days for staple removal Return to clinic in 1 week for blood pressure check Return to clinic in 4-6 weeks for your post partum and post operative visit.  Continue these medications: Percocet 5/325mg 1-2 tabs Orally every 4hrs as needed for moderate pain. Motrin 600mg Oral every 6 hrs. Colace 100mg Oral twice daily for constipation if needed. Continue taking a vitamin daily. Department of Obstetrics and Gynecology  Operative Note  Date of Surgery: [**DATE**]  Preoperative Diagnosis: 1) Prior cesarean times two  2) Singleton pregnancy at 38 weeks gestation  3) Maternal diabetes mellitus on insulin  4) Fetal cardiac defects (ASD, VSD, transposition of great vessels)  5) Undesired fertility  Postoperative Diagnosis: Same, abdomenal wall, omental adhesions  Procedure: repeat cesarean section  Surgeon: [**NAME**]     Assistant(s): [**NAME**]  Anesthesiologist: gibbs     Assistant: [**NAME**]  Anesthesia: spinal  Pathology: placenta; bilateral segments of fallopian tube  Volume Homeostasis: EBL: 800 ml IVF: 2100 ml Urine Out: 150 ml; cl;ear  History:  [**NAME**] is a 38 y.o.  at 38w6d G4 P2022 (post op).   Entry and Delivery:  Time-out confirmed patient and procedure.   It was confirmed that she had received her prophylactic antibiotics and that her sequential compression stockings were in place and functioning.   The patient was prepped and draped in a routine fashion for abdominal surgery. The abdomen was entered using a pffensteil skin incision.  Omental abdomenal wall adhesions were encountered along the midline and were removed with sharp dissection and the bovie.  In the lower aspect the omentum was protruding through a defect in the peritoneum. There was a need here to transect the omentum and suture ligate each end.  A bladder flap was created and then a transverse incision was made in the lower uterine segment with a scalpel and extended laterally with scissors and bluntly .  The above described infant was delivered from the Cephalic presentation.  The cord was clamped and cut and the baby handed to the pediatrician.  Blood for gases and DNA was obtained.  The placenta was delivered with cord traction.  The uterus was wiped out with a lap.  A parkland tubal ligation was performed without difficulty. There was good hemostasis.  Findings: Amniotic fluid was clear; Normal uterus, tubes and ovaries bilaterally.   Neonate:  Liveborn infant female weighing 3468 grams with Apgars of 8 and 9.  Cord Gases: Pending  Closure: The uterus was closed in a single layer closure using monocryl in a running and locking fashion.  The bladder flap  was not  closed. The abdomen was wiped of blood and blood clots. The fascia was closed with two suture/s of 0-Vicryl starting at the angle and running in a continuous fashion to the midline from each side. The subcutaneous tissue was irrigated and closed with vicryl suture.  The skin was closed with subcuticular monocryl.   The vagina was cleared of clots.  All counts were correct.  Patient was stable to recovery room and child was being cared for by the NICU team  [**NAME**], MD

Repeat Low Transverse C-section   Surgeons: Dr [**NAME**]  Assistants:   Anesthesia Attending:   Anesthesia Assistant:   Anesthesia:  General  EBL: 1000 cc  Fluids:   PRBC  Crystalloid 1500   Platelets  Other    Urinary Output:  200 cc  Drains: 1.foley to gravity  2. JP drain in subcutaneous space  Implants (include size & make): none  Specimens: Placenta;    Findings:  Normal;  Complications: The patient tolerated the procedure well with no complications.  Disposition: stable  Operative Report and Findings: The patient was taken to the operating room and there under spinal anesthesia her abdomen was draped and prepped in the usual sterile fashion.  A pfannenstiel incision was made through the previous old scar and the  various anatomical layers were dissected down to the layer of the parietal peritoneum.The parietal peritoneum was entered with aid of hemostats and Metzenbaum scissors. A bladder flap was established with aid of Metzenbaum scissors.  A transverse incision was made on the lower uterine segment and spread with blunt finger dissection.  A viable male infant was delivered  and handed to the NICU unit on standby.  The placenta was manually removed and the uterus was closed with a continuous interlocking layer of 0-PDS suture.  The uterine incision was then reinforced with a second continuous imbricating layer of 0-PDS.  The parietal peritoneum was then closed with a continuous layer of 000-vicryl.  The muscles was closed with 3 interrupted sutures of 000-vicryl.  The fascia was closed with a continuous layer of 0-PDS starting a suture from both corners of the incision.  The subcutaneous layer was closed with a continuous layer of 000-vicryl and a jackson-pratt drain was placed in the subcutaneous layer.  The skin was closed with a subcuticular stitch of 0000-proline suture.  The jackson pratt drain was sewn in with an interrupted suture of 000-nylon.  The incision was covered with a Derma bond dressing.  The patient tolerated the procedure well under spinal anesthesia.  She was taken to the recovery room in satisfactory condition. Extensive abdominal and pelvic adhesive disease  Operation Performed:  Repeat High Transverse Cesarean Section Bilateral tubal interruption - Modified Pomeroy on the left, Filshie clip placement on the right Extensive lysis of adhesions  Surgeon: [**NAME**]  Assisstant: [**NAME**]  Anesthesiologist: [**NAME**]  Anesthesiology Assisstant: [**NAME**]  Anesthesia: Epidural  Pathology: Placenta, portion of left fallopian tube  EBL: 1100 mL  UOP:  200 mL  Fluids:  4000 cc  Findings: Severe adhesive disease.  Bicornuate uterus with rudimentary right horn and pregnancy located in primary left horn, normal left tube and ovary.  Right tube and ovary obscured by adhesions.  Liveborn infant male weighing 3864 grams with Apgars of 8 and 9.  Bladder intact without spill of sterile milk after backfill at end of case.  Indication: [**NAME**] is a 37 y.o. female para 3104 at 37 weeks gestation who presented for scheduled repeat cesearean delivery and BTI.  Her pregnancy had been complicated by a history of 3 prior cesarean deliveries with high suspicion of severe adhesive disease, hypothyroidism, gestational diabetes, and a bicornuate uterus.  She was admitted to L&D and set up for surgery.  Procedure: After satisfactory anesthesia, the patient was prepped and draped in a routine fashion for abdominal surgery.  Time-out confirmed patient and procedure.  The abdomen was entered via a low midline vertical incision and dissected down to the level of the fascia with sharp dissection and cautery. The fascia was scored in the midline, grasped on either side with Allis clamps, and extended both superiorly and inferiorly with sharp dissection. The rectus muscles were separated just to the left of the midline until a small area of peritoneum was identified.  The peritoneum was entered with sharp dissection and lifted off of the underlying peritoneum.  Through the peritoneal defect, dense adhesions could be felt between the anterior uterine wall and the overlying omentum, anterior fascial sheath, and bladder.  The peritoneum was tented up off of the uterlying uterus with a hemostat and taken down layer-by-layer both superiorly and inferiorly with Metzenbaum scissors.  When more dense areas of omental adhesion were encountered, they were undermined, doubly clamped with Kellys, the intervening segment incised, and the remaining ends ligated with a combination of Haney stitches and free ties of 2-0 vicryl.  Great care was taken to ensure hemostasis of the remaining omentum both before and after the clamps were removed.  Adhesiolysis continued over the next ~60 minutes as attempts were made to clear an area of the anterior uterus large enough to perform the hysterotomy.  As adhesions were dissected near the lower uterine segment, the bladder was back-filled with 200cc of sterile saline so that the borders of the bladder could be identified and avoided.  The bladder was adhered low on the uterine segment, therefore this area was avoided at the time of hysterotomy.  Instead, a transverse incision was made slightly above the lower uterine segment with a scalpel and extended laterally with blunt dissection.  No uterine window was identified at the time of hysterotomy.  Amniotic fluid was clear at the time of rupture.  The above described infant was delivered from the Cephalic presentation and gave a spontaneous cry.  The cord was clamped and cut and the baby handed to the pediatrician.  A cord segment and blood for gases and DNA was obtained.   The placenta was delivered with cord traction.  During placental delivery, the uterus was inadvertently inverted then immediately replaced in the appropriate orientation.  The uterus was grasped with a moist lap, exteriorized, and wiped out with a lap.  Ringed forceps were placed on each corner of the hysterotomy.  The uterus was then closed in a double layer closure using two sutures of 0-vicryl. The initial layer was a running locked layer and the second layer was an imbricating layer.  Excellent hemostasis was achieved with a combination of cautery and figure-of-eight sutures as needed.  The uterine tone was noted to be slightly boggy, therefore 40 extra units of pitocin were added to the IVF by anesthesia, methergine was given IM, and 1000mg of cytotec were placed in the rectum after hysterotomy closure.  Uterine tone was noted to be significantly improved.  Attention was then turned to the tubal interruption. The left tube and ovary were easily identified and found to be normal.  A portion of the left tube was grasped with Babcocks and identified by its fimbriated end.  The mid-isthmic portion was pulled up into a loop and ligated with a tie of 0-plain gut suture. A small defect was made in the mesosalpinx underneath the loop and two segments of 0-chromic passed through on a hemostat.  Both sides of the loop were ligated and the intervening segment incised.  The lumen on either side was made hemostatic with cautery.  The right tube was much more difficult to identify as it originated from the rudimetary right horn of the bicornuate uterus.  The round ligament was identified and moved out of the way.  The other nearby tubular structure was grasped with a Babcock, and noted not to contain any vacular or urologic elements.  However, it was impossible to identify this structure as fallopian tube due to absence of visible fimbriae.  The decision was made to place a Filshie clip across a clear portion of this structure near the cornua of the rudimentary right horn. A single clip was loaded in the applicated and placed at a right angle across the tube.  The clip was then closed and the applicator removed.   The uterus was placed back into the peritoneal cavity. Copious irrigation was performed at the abdominal sidewalls and over the hysterotomy site.  The uterine incision was hemostatic and uterine tone adequate. The fascia, muscle, peritoneum, and areas of omental dissection were inspected extensively and were found to be intact and hemostatic.  The bladder was back-filled with 100cc of sterile milk and the pelvis was inspected for any leakage from bladder injury.  None was noted.  Urine in the foley was clear per anesthesia.  The fascia was closed with 2 sutures of 0-PDS starting at the angles and running in a continuous fashion to meet at the midline. The subcutaneous tissue was irrigated and then closed with a running stitch of 0-chromic.  The skin was closed with 4-0 monocryl.  Dermabond and a pressure dressing were applied.  The vagina was cleared of clots.  All counts were correct and the patient left for the recovery room in good condition.  No complications were encountered during the case. This note was copied from the chart of GIRL/Savanna Dye. Lactation:  Discharge rounding with 22-year-old mother and her newborn daughter born at 40 weeks 2 days gestation by SVD, weighing 2.235g.  Mother was adequately treated for CZ infection during pregnancy.  Baby had in utero tobacco exposure. Baby is not in mother's room due to a car seat challenge related to the baby's small size.  Mother reports baby is nursing well, and denies any nipple soreness during the feeds.   Mother does plan to work outside the home at some point, although she did not work outside the home with her first child who is now 15 months old.  Parents and their 15-month-old have been residing with the maternal grandparents here in [**LOCATION_CITY**].   Lactation history:  The older sibling was breastfed x 3 months.  Mother cites the difficulty at three months as a time when friends would frequently come by to visit without knocking, and she was uncomfortable nursing around others.  Mother also reports that she stopped breastfeeding suddenly at 3 months, and her breasts soon became "sunken in" for a time.  Maternal breast assessment:  Medium to large breasts are closely spaced and rounded, and the nipples are nonreddened and intact.   Discussion with recommendations:  We discussed the mother's first lactation experience and her sudden termination of breastfeeding, followed by a "sunken-in" appearance of her breasts for a period of time.  Mother was advised that this is referred to as breast involution, and frequently occurs when there is a sudden weaning versus a gradual weaning, though the mother's breasts typically return to their former tone within two to 3 menstrual cycles.   We discussed the expected onset of the mother's second milk, Lactogenesis II [L2], with the recommendation for frequent feeds to quickly address any breast engorgement.  Mother describes her previous lactation experience with breast engorgement as particularly dramatic, but improving within one to 2 days.  Mother was advised that this is the typical experience of most mothers, although a small number of mothers do experience a longer period of breast engorgement prior to its resolution.  Mother was reassured that the swelling with breast engorgement is many extra red blood cells and additional lymph fluid that supports the second milk coming in, but these extra fluids in the breasts are only needed to establish the second milk.  Continuation of the milk supply is based upon frequency of emptying the breasts, which stimulates frequent refill.    Mother is enrolled with WIC, and breastfeeding support was discussed through the WIC program.  Mother was provided with a pump kit as well as demonstration of the Medela Harmony manual pump, the type of pump the mother had used with her first child.  Mother was invited to our new mothers' breastfeeding support group, along with her children.
